# End of Chapter 5

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume II — Visual Language

# Chapter 6 — Typography System

---

# 6.1 Philosophy

Typography is the voice of Vivah.

Before users interact with buttons, animations, or imagery, they read.

Typography determines whether Vivah feels:

Trustworthy.

Elegant.

Warm.

Professional.

Or generic.

The typography system should feel inspired by premium wedding invitations, luxury publishing, and editorial design—not technology products.

Typography must communicate confidence without becoming ornamental.

---

# 6.2 Typography Principles

Typography should always prioritize:

Readability

↓

Hierarchy

↓

Rhythm

↓

Elegance

↓

Emotion

↓

Decoration

Decoration should never compromise readability.

---

# 6.3 Font Families

Vivah uses only **two font families**.

No third font is permitted.

---

## Display Typeface

Purpose

Large headings.

Hero.

Editorial titles.

Quotes.

Celebration moments.

Characteristics

Elegant.

Sophisticated.

High contrast.

Classic.

Timeless.

Recommended

* Cormorant Garamond
* Canela (Premium)
* EB Garamond
* Libre Baskerville

Primary Recommendation

**Cormorant Garamond**

---

## Interface Typeface

Purpose

Body text.

Navigation.

Forms.

Buttons.

Labels.

Cards.

Descriptions.

Characteristics

Highly readable.

Modern.

Neutral.

Friendly.

Recommended

* Inter
* Geist
* Manrope
* Plus Jakarta Sans

Primary Recommendation

**Inter**

---

# 6.4 Typography Personality

Display Typeface should feel

Elegant.

Expressive.

Romantic.

Literary.

Timeless.

Interface Typeface should feel

Reliable.

Professional.

Comfortable.

Quiet.

Invisible.

The interface font should never draw attention to itself.

---

# 6.5 Font Weight System

Display

300

400

500

Never use 700+

Interface

400

500

600

700

Avoid ultra-bold headings.

Luxury typography relies on spacing, not weight.

---

# 6.6 Heading Scale

## Display XXL

Hero Title

```text
72px
Desktop

56px
Laptop

44px
Tablet

36px
Mobile
```

---

## Display XL

Major Sections

```text
56px

48px

40px

32px
```

---

## Display Large

Editorial Sections

```text
44px

40px

34px

28px
```

---

## Heading 1

```text
36px

32px

28px

24px
```

---

## Heading 2

```text
30px

28px

24px

22px
```

---

## Heading 3

```text
24px

22px

20px

18px
```

---

## Heading 4

```text
20px

18px

18px

16px
```

---

# 6.7 Body Scale

Large

20px

Regular

18px

Normal

16px

Small

14px

Caption

12px

Never use body text smaller than 14px.

---

# 6.8 Line Heights

Display

110%

Editorial

120%

Body

160%

Captions

150%

Buttons

100%

Forms

150%

Good typography breathes.

---

# 6.9 Letter Spacing

Display

-0.03em

Headings

-0.02em

Body

0

Buttons

0.02em

Uppercase Labels

0.12em

Luxury typography is achieved through spacing, not boldness.

---

# 6.10 Paragraph Width

Maximum reading width

```text
70 characters
```

Ideal

```text
55–65 characters
```

Never allow large blocks of text stretching across the screen.

Reading comfort increases trust.

---

# 6.11 Text Alignment

Default

Left

Hero

Centered (Desktop)

Left (Mobile)

Quotes

Centered

Forms

Left

Never justify text.

Never mix alignment unnecessarily.

---

# 6.12 Hierarchy Rules

One page should contain:

One H1

↓

Several H2

↓

Supporting H3

↓

Body

↓

Captions

Avoid using multiple display headings on one screen.

Hierarchy should be immediately obvious.

---

# 6.13 Hero Typography

Hero should prioritize emotion.

Example hierarchy

```text
Display XXL

↓

Supporting paragraph

↓

Primary CTA

↓

Secondary CTA
```

Never overload the hero with text.

Maximum

Headline

2 lines

Supporting paragraph

3 lines

---

# 6.14 Navigation Typography

Navigation must be understated.

16px

Medium

No uppercase.

No excessive spacing.

Professional.

---

# 6.15 Button Typography

Buttons communicate action.

Weight

600

Size

16px

Letter spacing

0.02em

Avoid oversized buttons.

Avoid tiny labels.

---

# 6.16 Form Typography

Labels

14px

Medium

Input

16px

Placeholder

16px

Muted

Helper Text

14px

Error

14px

Readable forms reduce anxiety.

---

# 6.17 Card Typography

Profile Name

24px

Display

Occupation

16px

Metadata

14px

Values

16px

Bio

16px

Everything should feel balanced.

---

# 6.18 Quotes

Quotes should use Display Typeface.

Centered.

Large quotation marks.

Generous whitespace.

No decorative borders.

Example

> "Meaningful relationships begin with understanding."

---

# 6.19 Numbers

Use tabular numbers where appropriate.

Statistics

Memberships

Payments

Profile completion

Age

Distance

Dates

Numbers should align correctly.

---

# 6.20 Emphasis Rules

Prefer emphasis using

Weight

Spacing

Hierarchy

Color

Avoid

Underline

Excessive italics

Bold paragraphs

Multiple emphasis styles together

---

# 6.21 Capitalization Rules

Navigation

Title Case

Buttons

Title Case

Headings

Sentence Case

Forms

Sentence Case

Errors

Sentence Case

Avoid ALL CAPS except small labels.

---

# 6.22 Typography Rhythm

Spacing between headings and paragraphs should follow a consistent rhythm.

Example

```text
H1

↓

32px

↓

Paragraph

↓

24px

↓

Button

↓

64px

↓

Next Section
```

Rhythm creates elegance.

---

# 6.23 White Space Around Text

Never crowd typography.

Every heading requires breathing room.

Every paragraph requires visual separation.

Every section begins with generous whitespace.

Whitespace improves perceived quality.

---

# 6.24 Typography in Motion

Text animations should feel refined.

Allowed

Fade

Rise

Opacity

Small blur

Very subtle tracking changes

Forbidden

Bounce

Spin

Rotate

Explode

Elastic text

Typing every heading

Text should never become entertainment.

---

# 6.25 Accessibility

Minimum body size

16px preferred

14px minimum

Contrast

WCAG AA minimum

Selectable text

Always enabled

Zoom

200%

Typography should remain readable.

---

# 6.26 Typography Anti-Patterns

Never use

More than two fonts

Outlined text

Gradient text

Glow text

Drop-shadow text

Compressed fonts

Decorative script fonts

Wedding invitation calligraphy

All caps headings

Tiny captions

Typography should remain timeless.

---

# 6.27 Typography Tokens

```css
--font-display

--font-body

--font-size-display-xxl

--font-size-display-xl

--font-size-h1

--font-size-h2

--font-size-h3

--font-size-body-lg

--font-size-body

--font-size-small

--font-size-caption

--line-height-display

--line-height-body

--tracking-display

--tracking-body
```

Every component must use tokens.

Hardcoded font sizes are prohibited.

---

# 6.28 Typography Review Checklist

Before approving typography:

□ Is the hierarchy immediately obvious?

□ Can the page be scanned in under five seconds?

□ Is the body text comfortable to read?

□ Is there enough whitespace?

□ Are only two font families used?

□ Is emphasis restrained?

□ Does the typography feel timeless?

□ Would this still look elegant if all colors became grayscale?

If the answer to any question is "No," revise the typography.

---

# End of Chapter 6

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume II — Visual Language

# Chapter 7 — Layout & Spatial System

---

# 7.1 Philosophy

The layout system is the invisible architecture of Vivah.

Users rarely notice good layouts.

They immediately notice poor ones.

A premium experience is not created through decoration.

It is created through proportion.

Alignment.

Rhythm.

Balance.

Breathing room.

Every screen should feel as though it was designed by an architect rather than assembled by a developer.

---

# 7.2 The Architectural Grid

Vivah follows a **12-column responsive grid**.

Desktop

```text
12 Columns
80px Gutters
Max Width: 1440px
```

Laptop

```text
12 Columns
64px Gutters
Max Width: 1280px
```

Tablet

```text
8 Columns
32px Gutters
```

Mobile

```text
4 Columns
20px Gutters
```

The grid is never visible but always respected.

---

# 7.3 Container Widths

Extra Small

480px

Small

640px

Medium

768px

Large

1024px

XL

1280px

2XL

1440px

Never allow content to stretch endlessly.

Reading comfort always takes priority.

---

# 7.4 Vertical Rhythm

Every page follows a consistent vertical rhythm.

Small Section

80px

Medium Section

120px

Large Section

180px

Hero

Minimum 100vh

Luxury is often defined by generous spacing.

Never compress sections simply to reduce scrolling.

---

# 7.5 Spatial Hierarchy

Each page consists of four layers.

Layer One

Background

↓

Layer Two

Architecture

↓

Layer Three

Content

↓

Layer Four

Interaction

These layers should never compete.

---

# 7.6 Page Composition

Every screen should follow this order.

Navigation

↓

Hero / Title

↓

Primary Content

↓

Supporting Content

↓

Call To Action

↓

Footer

Avoid random ordering.

Users should always know where they are.

---

# 7.7 Alignment Rules

Everything aligns.

Cards.

Buttons.

Images.

Headings.

Inputs.

Icons.

Alignment is one of the strongest signals of craftsmanship.

Never align elements "by eye."

Use the grid.

---

# 7.8 The Rule of Three

Every screen should establish three visual levels.

Primary Focus

↓

Supporting Content

↓

Background Context

If everything is equally important,

nothing is important.

---

# 7.9 Whitespace Philosophy

Whitespace is an active design element.

Whitespace creates:

Trust

Luxury

Readability

Focus

Calm

Never treat empty space as unused space.

Whitespace is intentional.

---

# 7.10 Margins

Desktop Outer Margin

80px

Laptop

64px

Tablet

40px

Mobile

20px

No content should touch the edge of the viewport.

---

# 7.11 Section Spacing

Between Major Sections

160px

Between Minor Sections

96px

Between Cards

32px

Between Text Blocks

24px

Between Labels and Inputs

12px

Consistency creates rhythm.

---

# 7.12 Card Layout

Every card follows a consistent internal spacing system.

Padding

32px

Gap Between Elements

16px

Image Radius

20px

Content Width

Comfortable reading line

Cards should feel like carefully designed printed pieces.

Not containers.

---

# 7.13 Image Placement

Images should support layout.

Not dominate it.

Preferred Ratios

16:9

4:3

3:4

Square

Avoid unusual crops.

Never stretch images.

---

# 7.14 Hero Layout

The hero is not another section.

It is an introduction.

Structure

```text
Navigation

↓

Atmosphere

↓

Headline

↓

Supporting Text

↓

Primary CTA

↓

Secondary CTA

↓

Subtle Visual Cue
```

No more than two CTAs.

No information overload.

---

# 7.15 Content Width

Maximum paragraph width

680px

Maximum hero width

760px

Maximum article width

720px

Never create walls of text.

---

# 7.16 Symmetry vs Asymmetry

Vivah primarily uses balanced asymmetry.

Perfect symmetry feels ceremonial.

Extreme asymmetry feels chaotic.

The goal is controlled balance.

---

# 7.17 Flow

Every page should guide the eye naturally.

Top

↓

Headline

↓

Visual

↓

Supporting Information

↓

Primary Action

↓

Next Section

Users should never wonder where to look next.

---

# 7.18 Layering

Layers create depth.

Background

↓

Soft Lighting

↓

Decorative Elements

↓

Cards

↓

Interactive Components

↓

Floating Elements

Never exceed six visual layers.

Complexity reduces clarity.

---

# 7.19 Component Density

Vivah is intentionally spacious.

Preferred density

Low

This creates calm.

Avoid packing multiple controls into one area.

Users should never feel rushed.

---

# 7.20 Corner Radius System

Small

8px

Medium

12px

Large

20px

Extra Large

28px

Never mix arbitrary radii.

Rounded corners should feel soft but mature.

Avoid pill-shaped components unless specifically required.

---

# 7.21 Elevation System

Vivah uses restrained elevation.

Level 0

Flat

Level 1

Soft Border

Level 2

Very Soft Shadow

Level 3

Card Hover

Level 4

Dialog

No dramatic floating effects.

Elevation should feel natural.

---

# 7.22 Section Identity

Every section should have its own atmosphere.

Not by changing layout.

But by changing:

Light

Material

Illustration

Photography

Color temperature

Spacing

Never by changing overall structure.

Consistency comes first.

---

# 7.23 Responsive Philosophy

Responsive design is not resizing.

It is redesigning.

Desktop

Immersive.

Tablet

Focused.

Mobile

Essential.

Every breakpoint should feel intentionally designed.

---

# 7.24 Visual Anchors

Each screen should contain one visual anchor.

Examples

A photograph.

An illustration.

A profile.

A quote.

A meaningful object.

Never allow multiple competing anchors.

---

# 7.25 Scroll Rhythm

Scrolling should feel like walking.

Not flipping pages.

Every major section should introduce one new idea.

Avoid abrupt transitions.

Use visual continuity.

---

# 7.26 Decorative Placement

Decorative elements belong at the edges.

Examples

Top corners

Bottom corners

Margins

Section transitions

Never place decoration directly behind important text.

---

# 7.27 Background Architecture

Backgrounds should consist of multiple subtle layers.

Example

```text
Ambient Light

↓

Soft Texture

↓

Decorative Illustration

↓

Content Surface

↓

Content
```

Avoid flat colors.

Avoid busy imagery.

---

# 7.28 Empty States

Empty states deserve as much attention as populated screens.

Every empty state should include

Illustration

Message

Guidance

Primary Action

Never leave users facing blank pages.

---

# 7.29 Scroll Breaks

Every 2–3 viewport heights, introduce a visual reset.

Examples

A quote.

A full-width image.

A meaningful story.

A transition.

This prevents visual fatigue.

---

# 7.30 Layout Anti-Patterns

Never use

Full-width paragraphs

Random spacing

Misaligned cards

Inconsistent gutters

Floating components without purpose

Tiny margins

Edge-to-edge text

Overlapping sections for decoration

Uneven rhythm

Broken grids

Every layout decision should strengthen order.

---

# 7.31 Layout Tokens

```css
--container-xs

--container-sm

--container-md

--container-lg

--container-xl

--container-2xl

--space-4

--space-8

--space-12

--space-16

--space-24

--space-32

--space-48

--space-64

--space-96

--space-128

--radius-sm

--radius-md

--radius-lg

--radius-xl
```

All spacing and sizing must reference tokens.

No arbitrary values.

---

# 7.32 Layout Review Checklist

Before approving any layout:

□ Is the visual hierarchy immediately clear?

□ Is whitespace being used intentionally?

□ Does the layout follow the grid?

□ Are all alignments precise?

□ Is there only one visual anchor?

□ Is scrolling comfortable?

□ Does the page feel calm?

□ Does the page breathe?

□ Does every section have enough room?

□ Does the layout still work without images?

If any answer is "No," revise the layout before implementation.

---

# End of Chapter 7

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume II — Visual Language

# Chapter 8 — Material & Surface Language

---

# 8.1 Philosophy

A digital interface has no physical weight.

Yet the human brain constantly interprets digital objects as physical materials.

Vivah deliberately borrows from tactile materials because they evoke familiarity, warmth, craftsmanship, and permanence.

The interface should never feel like pixels floating on a screen.

It should feel as though every surface has been carefully crafted.

Every material exists to communicate trust.

---

# 8.2 Material Hierarchy

Vivah uses six primary materials.

They appear in a strict hierarchy.

1. Handmade Paper
2. Fine Linen
3. Soft Marble
4. Warm Stone
5. Brushed Champagne Metal
6. Clear Glass

No additional material language should be introduced without expanding this document.

---

# 8.3 Handmade Paper

Paper represents beginnings.

Letters.

Invitations.

Stories.

Commitment.

It becomes the emotional foundation of Vivah.

Applications

* Hero backgrounds
* Large content sections
* Editorial layouts
* Storytelling pages
* Success stories

Characteristics

Very subtle grain.

Almost invisible.

Warm.

Matte.

Never glossy.

Never textured enough to interfere with readability.

---

# 8.4 Fine Linen

Linen communicates elegance without extravagance.

Applications

Cards

Forms

Authentication

Profile summaries

Dialogs

Properties

Soft.

Natural.

Light.

Comfortable.

Never patterned.

Never decorative.

---

# 8.5 Marble

Marble represents permanence.

It should appear only during meaningful moments.

Examples

Premium Membership

Wedding Journey

Celebration

Major Success States

Certificates

Avoid using marble everywhere.

Too much marble destroys exclusivity.

---

# 8.6 Natural Stone

Stone represents trust.

Grounding.

Longevity.

Architecture.

Stone should influence:

Section backgrounds.

Large illustrations.

Structural framing.

Never decorative ornaments.

---

# 8.7 Champagne Metal

Metal communicates craftsmanship.

Not wealth.

It replaces traditional "gold."

Applications

Borders

Icons

Premium badges

Buttons

Navigation highlights

Focus rings

Avoid

Large metallic gradients.

Shiny gold surfaces.

Mirror effects.

Heavy reflections.

---

# 8.8 Glass

Glass should feel invisible.

Its purpose is to separate.

Not decorate.

Allowed

Navigation

Dialogs

Dropdowns

Floating menus

Search overlay

Profile quick previews

Avoid

Glass cards everywhere.

Glass buttons.

Glass forms.

Glass overload.

Vivah is not a glassmorphism product.

---

# 8.9 Fabric

Fabric inspiration comes from:

Silk

Cotton

Wedding drapery

Curtains

Not because fabric should be visible,

but because spacing should feel soft.

Fabric influences

Movement.

Spacing.

Corners.

Transitions.

Not textures.

---

# 8.10 Wood

Wood appears sparingly.

It represents home.

Family.

Warmth.

Applications

Illustrations.

Photography.

Background environments.

Never UI controls.

---

# 8.11 Ceramic

Ceramic represents calm domestic life.

Coffee cups.

Dinner plates.

Family dining.

Morning routines.

Ceramic appears only in photography and illustrations.

Never interface elements.

---

# 8.12 Floral Materials

Flowers are not decorative objects.

Flowers communicate celebration.

Freshness.

Growth.

Hope.

Flowers should always appear fresh.

Never artificial.

Preferred flowers

White Roses

Jasmine

Baby's Breath

Hydrangea

White Orchids

Peonies

Avoid

Bright marigold overload.

Artificial bouquets.

Heavy garlands.

Festival decoration.

---

# 8.13 Surface Hierarchy

Every page follows this surface order.

```text
Environment

↓

Architecture

↓

Primary Surface

↓

Secondary Surface

↓

Interactive Surface

↓

Floating Surface
```

Each layer should remain visually distinct.

---

# 8.14 Primary Surface

Purpose

Main content.

Background.

Large sections.

Characteristics

Warm.

Flat.

Paper inspired.

Very low contrast.

---

# 8.15 Secondary Surface

Purpose

Cards.

Forms.

Containers.

Characteristics

Slight elevation.

Minimal border.

Soft shadow.

Never floating dramatically.

---

# 8.16 Floating Surface

Purpose

Menus.

Dialogs.

Dropdowns.

Notifications.

Characteristics

Slight glass.

Blur.

Very soft shadow.

Maximum elevation level.

Used sparingly.

---

# 8.17 Border Philosophy

Borders should almost disappear.

Preferred

1px

Low opacity.

Warm gray.

Champagne.

Never

Dark borders.

Heavy outlines.

Black strokes.

---

# 8.18 Shadow Philosophy

Vivah uses ambient shadows.

Not dramatic shadows.

Level 1

Almost invisible.

Level 2

Card.

Level 3

Hover.

Level 4

Dialog.

No layer should appear to float unrealistically.

Shadows create depth.

Not spectacle.

---

# 8.19 Corner Philosophy

Corners should feel crafted.

Small components

8px

Cards

16px

Dialogs

20px

Large panels

24px

Never exceed 32px.

Avoid circular UI everywhere.

---

# 8.20 Surface Temperature

Every material should feel warm.

Even white should feel warm.

Avoid

Cool whites.

Blue grays.

Cold neutrals.

Harsh black.

Warmth builds trust.

---

# 8.21 Environmental Surfaces

The background environment changes subtly throughout the experience.

Morning

Soft ivory.

Noon

Bright linen.

Evening

Champagne warmth.

Celebration

Warm marble.

Never dramatic color shifts.

Only atmospheric changes.

---

# 8.22 Texture Rules

Textures should remain subconscious.

Users should notice them only after extended observation.

Maximum opacity

4%

Preferred

2%

Avoid

Visible repeating patterns.

Noise overlays.

Paper scans.

Heavy grain.

---

# 8.23 Reflection Rules

Reflections should imitate natural light.

Allowed

Soft edge reflections.

Warm highlights.

Window light.

Avoid

Mirror reflections.

Chrome effects.

Artificial lens flares.

---

# 8.24 Decorative Metal

Champagne metal should appear only where craftsmanship matters.

Examples

Premium badge.

Verified badge.

Buttons.

Section dividers.

Navigation underline.

Never decorate entire layouts with metallic effects.

---

# 8.25 Surface Motion

Materials should react naturally.

Examples

Light shifting.

Very subtle highlight movement.

Ambient reflection.

Soft hover elevation.

No exaggerated movement.

Materials should feel alive.

Not animated.

---

# 8.26 Surface Aging

Every surface should appear timeless.

Avoid textures or effects that feel trendy.

Ask

Would this still look premium in ten years?

If uncertain,

simplify it.

---

# 8.27 Accessibility

Material effects must never reduce readability.

Blur

Never below accessibility thresholds.

Textures

Must not interfere with text.

Shadows

Must never reduce contrast.

Glass

Must always preserve readability.

---

# 8.28 Material Anti-Patterns

Never use

Chrome

Mirror glass

Liquid glass

Heavy frosted glass

Plastic gradients

Neon reflections

Glossy cards

Carbon fiber

Carbon textures

Leather textures

Wood UI

Heavy embossing

Excessive bevels

Luxury is achieved through restraint.

---

# 8.29 Material Tokens

```css
--surface-primary

--surface-secondary

--surface-floating

--surface-premium

--material-paper

--material-linen

--material-marble

--material-stone

--material-metal

--shadow-1

--shadow-2

--shadow-3

--shadow-4

--border-subtle

--border-premium
```

Every component must consume material tokens.

Never hardcode shadows or borders.

---

# 8.30 Material Review Checklist

Before approving any design:

□ Does every surface feel intentional?

□ Is warmth maintained?

□ Are textures subtle?

□ Are shadows restrained?

□ Does the interface avoid looking artificial?

□ Is glass used only where appropriate?

□ Does every material support trust?

□ Could this design exist as a beautifully crafted physical object?

If any answer is "No,"

the material system requires refinement.

---

# End of Chapter 8

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume II — Visual Language

# Chapter 9 — Floral Language System

---

# 9.1 Philosophy

Flowers are one of the oldest symbols of celebration.

However, within Vivah they are **not decoration**.

They are part of the visual language.

Flowers represent:

New beginnings.

Hope.

Growth.

Purity.

Blessings.

Grace.

They should never dominate the interface.

Flowers should feel like architecture.

Not wallpaper.

---

# 9.2 Core Principle

Flowers should **frame experiences**.

They should never become the experience.

A visitor should remember

the story,

the profile,

the typography,

the interaction.

Not the flowers.

---

# 9.3 Floral Density

Vivah follows a Floral Density Scale.

Level 0

No flowers.

Level 1

Tiny botanical accents.

Level 2

Corner compositions.

Level 3

Section framing.

Level 4

Celebration pages only.

The homepage should mostly remain between Level 1 and Level 2.

Only special experiences may reach Level 3.

Level 4 is reserved for engagement or wedding success stories.

---

# 9.4 Floral Placement

Flowers belong only in architectural positions.

Preferred

Top corners.

Bottom corners.

Side framing.

Section dividers.

Large empty backgrounds.

Illustrations.

Avoid

Behind paragraphs.

Behind buttons.

Behind forms.

Behind profile information.

Behind navigation.

Around cards.

Flowers must never interfere with usability.

---

# 9.5 Botanical Palette

Preferred flowers

White Rose

Baby's Breath

Jasmine

Peony

Hydrangea

White Orchid

Tulip

Magnolia

Lotus (very limited)

Preferred leaves

Eucalyptus

Olive

Soft Fern

Sage

Avoid

Bright marigolds.

Red roses everywhere.

Festival garlands.

Heavy floral walls.

Artificial bouquets.

Large colorful arrangements.

---

# 9.6 Color Rules

Flowers should always remain desaturated.

Preferred colors

Ivory

Cream

Soft blush

Warm white

Dusty pink

Muted peach

Very light lavender

Muted sage

Never use

Neon flowers.

Bright reds.

Hot pink.

Orange-heavy palettes.

Artificial saturation.

---

# 9.7 Illustration Style

Floral illustrations should feel

Handcrafted.

Watercolor-inspired.

Minimal.

Organic.

Elegant.

Never

Cartoon.

Clipart.

Vector sticker.

Emoji-like.

The illustration style should resemble artwork printed on premium wedding stationery.

---

# 9.8 Photography Rules

When photography includes flowers

Flowers should support people.

Not replace them.

Preferred

Bouquet on table.

Window flowers.

Garden path.

Soft floral arrangements.

Single flower.

Avoid

Massive flower walls.

Wedding stage flowers.

Artificial decoration.

Balloon flowers.

---

# 9.9 Botanical Motion

Flowers should move naturally.

Examples

Gentle sway.

Very slow breathing.

Light response.

Tiny petal movement.

Never

Bounce.

Rotate.

Float endlessly.

Explode.

Spin.

Motion should imitate wind.

---

# 9.10 Petals

Petals are used sparingly.

Only during

Landing Hero.

Major celebrations.

Success stories.

Special transitions.

Maximum

3–6 visible petals.

Never create "petal rain."

Avoid movie-style dramatic effects.

---

# 9.11 Vines

Vines replace ordinary dividers.

Instead of

────────────

Vivah may use

Very thin botanical lines.

Minimal vines.

Elegant curves.

Never thick branches.

Never decorative vines covering the interface.

---

# 9.12 Floral Architecture

Flowers should create spatial framing.

Example

```text
╭ 🌿                    🌿 ╮

         Content

╰ 🌿                    🌿 ╯
```

Not

```text
🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸

TEXT

🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸🌸
```

Whitespace remains dominant.

---

# 9.13 Seasonal Behaviour

Spring

More blossoms.

Summer

More greenery.

Monsoon

Deeper leaves.

Autumn

Warmer petals.

Winter

Minimal flowers.

Only decorative illustrations should adapt.

The interface itself remains consistent.

---

# 9.14 Floral Identity

Flowers should become part of the Vivah brand.

Not random assets.

Every flower illustration should follow one illustration language.

One brush style.

One stroke weight.

One color system.

Consistency is mandatory.

---

# 9.15 Hero Usage

Hero flowers should frame.

Never cover.

Recommended

Top corners.

Bottom edges.

Soft depth.

Light overlap.

The hero headline must remain visually dominant.

---

# 9.16 Profile Pages

Profiles should contain almost no flowers.

Reason

Profiles represent people.

Flowers should never distract from them.

Allowed

Tiny divider.

Small botanical accent.

Verification illustration.

Nothing more.

---

# 9.17 Authentication

Authentication pages should remain calm.

One botanical illustration.

Large whitespace.

No decorative overload.

Focus remains on trust.

---

# 9.18 Celebration Pages

These pages may use the highest floral density.

Examples

Engagement.

Wedding.

Anniversary.

Success Story.

Even here,

flowers should frame,

not consume.

---

# 9.19 Empty States

Instead of generic illustrations,

empty states may use

Tiny botanical sketches.

Example

A single branch.

A flower bud.

Growing leaves.

This communicates hope rather than emptiness.

---

# 9.20 Section Dividers

Flowers should occasionally become transitions.

Example

```text
─────────────

🌿

─────────────
```

Or

Soft botanical curves.

Never use flowers on every divider.

---

# 9.21 Decorative Limits

Every page should ask

How many flowers are currently visible?

If the answer exceeds

approximately 15% of the visible area,

reduce them.

Flowers support.

They never dominate.

---

# 9.22 Backgrounds

Backgrounds may include

Very subtle botanical silhouettes.

Opacity

1–3%

Never visible enough to compete with typography.

---

# 9.23 Accessibility

Decorative flowers must

Never reduce contrast.

Never overlap interactive components.

Never interfere with keyboard focus.

Never block screen readers.

Botanical decoration is always ignored by assistive technologies.

---

# 9.24 Floral Anti-Patterns

Reject immediately

Wedding stage replicas.

Heavy floral arches.

Banquet hall decoration.

Clipart flowers.

Animated bouquets.

Rose petals everywhere.

Repeating floral wallpaper.

Symmetrical floral borders.

Bright red romance imagery.

Artificial flower PNGs.

Excessive botanical shadows.

Anything that resembles invitation templates from the early 2000s.

---

# 9.25 Floral Review Checklist

Before approving any design

□ Are flowers supporting the interface?

□ Is whitespace still dominant?

□ Is typography unobstructed?

□ Are flowers restrained?

□ Does the page still work without flowers?

□ Are flowers communicating elegance rather than decoration?

□ Would the page still feel premium if floral elements were reduced by half?

If the answer is "No" to any question,

the floral language needs refinement.

---

# End of Chapter 9

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume II — Visual Language

# Chapter 10 — Light, Atmosphere & Environmental Design

---

# 10.1 Philosophy

Light is the most important visual material in Vivah.

Before users notice typography, colors, flowers, or animations, they subconsciously perceive light.

Light determines emotional temperature.

It communicates:

Hope.

Warmth.

Safety.

Elegance.

New beginnings.

Every screen should appear naturally illuminated.

Never artificially lit.

---

# 10.2 The Role of Light

Light is never decoration.

Light performs four functions.

Guide attention.

↓

Create depth.

↓

Build atmosphere.

↓

Support emotion.

If light does not perform one of these functions,

it should be removed.

---

# 10.3 Natural Light

Vivah always prefers natural light.

Reference sources

Morning sunlight

Window light

Golden hour

Soft skylight

Open courtyard lighting

Filtered daylight

Never imitate

Studio flash

Nightclub lighting

LED strips

Neon

Sci-fi glows

Artificial spotlights

---

# 10.4 Emotional Lighting

Every page should communicate one emotional temperature.

Arrival

Hope

↓

Discovery

Warm curiosity

↓

Profiles

Clarity

↓

Messages

Comfort

↓

Success

Celebration

↓

Footer

Peace

Lighting should evolve gently throughout the journey.

---

# 10.5 Time of Day

Vivah exists in an eternal golden morning.

Not sunrise.

Not sunset.

A calm morning.

This creates optimism without drama.

Characteristics

Soft shadows.

Warm whites.

Long light gradients.

Gentle highlights.

Fresh atmosphere.

---

# 10.6 Color Temperature

Preferred

3200K–4500K

Warm neutral.

Avoid

Cold blue lighting.

Pure white.

Overly orange lighting.

The interface should never feel sterile.

---

# 10.7 Direction of Light

Primary light should always originate from above.

Prefer

Upper left

Upper center

Window lighting

Avoid

Multiple competing directions.

Conflicting shadows.

Inconsistent highlights.

Consistency creates realism.

---

# 10.8 Shadow Philosophy

Shadows are caused by light.

Not decoration.

Every shadow should suggest

Distance.

Weight.

Depth.

Hierarchy.

Avoid decorative shadows.

---

# 10.9 Ambient Glow

Ambient glow replaces excessive gradients.

Characteristics

Large.

Soft.

Diffused.

Invisible edges.

Low opacity.

Purpose

Create atmosphere.

Not attention.

---

# 10.10 Background Illumination

Backgrounds should never appear flat.

Preferred layering

```text id="yd1qyb"
Ambient Light

↓

Soft Gradient

↓

Paper Texture

↓

Architecture

↓

Content
```

Each layer should remain subtle.

---

# 10.11 Hero Lighting

The hero should feel like standing near a large window.

Characteristics

Bright center.

Soft corners.

Natural highlights.

Comfortable contrast.

Never use spotlight effects.

The hero should invite,

not perform.

---

# 10.12 Section Lighting

Every major section has its own atmosphere.

Story Section

Soft daylight.

Discovery

Warm ivory.

Profiles

Balanced neutral.

Families

Indoor warmth.

Celebration

Golden glow.

Footer

Evening warmth.

Transitions should remain subtle.

---

# 10.13 Glass Lighting

Whenever glass appears,

its lighting should imitate real glass.

Characteristics

Soft edge highlights.

Subtle reflections.

Blur.

Warm transparency.

Never

Mirror reflections.

Chrome.

Sharp glare.

---

# 10.14 Metallic Highlights

Champagne accents should catch light naturally.

Examples

Navigation underline.

Premium badge.

Buttons.

Icons.

The highlight should be visible only when needed.

Avoid permanent shine.

---

# 10.15 Illustration Lighting

All illustrations must follow one lighting system.

Single light source.

Soft shadows.

Warm palette.

Consistent direction.

No conflicting illumination.

---

# 10.16 Photography Lighting

Photography should feel naturally lit.

Preferred

Window light.

Golden hour.

Cloudy daylight.

Open shade.

Soft interiors.

Avoid

Flash photography.

High contrast studio lighting.

Artificial HDR.

Oversaturated editing.

---

# 10.17 Motion of Light

Light itself may move.

Very slowly.

Examples

Morning light drifting.

Window reflection changing.

Sunlight passing through fabric.

Tiny environmental changes.

Motion duration

20–60 seconds.

Almost imperceptible.

---

# 10.18 Environmental Depth

Depth is created through light.

Not blur.

Layer order

Foreground

↓

Interactive Layer

↓

Content

↓

Architecture

↓

Light

↓

Background

Never fake depth using excessive shadows.

---

# 10.19 Reflection Rules

Reflections should imitate physical reality.

Allowed

Window reflection.

Soft metallic edge.

Very subtle glass reflection.

Forbidden

Lens flare.

Mirror reflection.

Animated glare.

Rainbow reflections.

---

# 10.20 Atmospheric Particles

Particles are environmental.

Examples

Tiny dust.

Floating pollen.

Very small petals.

Maximum density

Extremely low.

Users should notice them only after spending time on the page.

Never use particles for spectacle.

---

# 10.21 Seasonal Atmosphere

Spring

More daylight.

Summer

Slightly brighter.

Monsoon

Softer light.

Autumn

Warmer tones.

Winter

Creamy interiors.

Changes should remain almost invisible.

---

# 10.22 Environmental Motion

The environment should breathe.

Curtains.

Light.

Leaves.

Reflections.

Shadows.

Nothing else.

Avoid excessive movement.

Stillness communicates confidence.

---

# 10.23 Weather

Vivah should always feel pleasant.

Never introduce

Storms.

Heavy rain.

Snow.

Lightning.

Fog.

Dark clouds.

Weather should never influence usability.

---

# 10.24 Darkness

Darkness exists only to create contrast.

Never create dark emotional experiences.

Dark elements should support readability,

not mood.

Vivah is fundamentally a light product.

---

# 10.25 Performance

Environmental lighting must remain inexpensive.

Prefer

CSS gradients.

Layered backgrounds.

Opacity transitions.

Transform animations.

Avoid

Canvas lighting.

Real-time rendering.

Heavy particle engines.

Expensive blur filters.

Luxury should not compromise performance.

---

# 10.26 Accessibility

Lighting should never reduce readability.

Background illumination must always maintain contrast.

Decorative glows must never interfere with text.

Motion must respect reduced-motion preferences.

---

# 10.27 Light Anti-Patterns

Reject

Blue glows.

Neon.

Cyber lighting.

Lens flare.

Laser effects.

Spotlights.

Artificial halos.

Animated sunshine.

High-intensity bloom.

Overexposed backgrounds.

Movie-style dramatic lighting.

Vivah is not cinematic.

It is atmospheric.

---

# 10.28 Lighting Tokens

```css id="zyr1ik"
--ambient-light

--ambient-light-warm

--ambient-light-soft

--shadow-soft

--shadow-medium

--shadow-dialog

--highlight-metal

--highlight-glass

--glow-subtle

--glow-premium
```

All lighting values must use tokens.

No arbitrary shadows or glow values.

---

# 10.29 Review Checklist

Before approving any environment

□ Does the lighting feel natural?

□ Is there only one primary light source?

□ Does the page feel warm?

□ Is atmosphere subtle?

□ Are shadows believable?

□ Does light improve hierarchy?

□ Would the page still feel elegant without animations?

□ Does lighting support trust?

□ Is performance preserved?

If any answer is "No,"

the environmental design requires refinement.

---

# End of Chapter 10

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume II — Visual Language

# Chapter 11 — Iconography & Symbol System

---

# 11.1 Philosophy

Icons exist to improve understanding.

They are not decoration.

An icon should never require explanation.

If an icon is confusing,

replace it.

Vivah uses icons to reduce cognitive load, reinforce meaning, and improve scanning—not to decorate the interface.

---

# 11.2 Icon Personality

Vivah icons should feel:

Elegant.

Minimal.

Human.

Timeless.

Quiet.

Confident.

Professional.

Avoid icons that feel:

Playful.

Corporate.

Gaming-inspired.

Futuristic.

Cartoonish.

Aggressive.

---

# 11.3 Icon Style

Vivah follows a **single icon language** throughout the product.

Preferred style:

Outlined icons.

Rounded joins.

Rounded line caps.

Simple geometry.

Minimal detail.

No excessive curves.

No sharp edges.

Recommended icon libraries:

* Lucide
* Phosphor (Regular only)
* Remix Icons (Outlined subset)

Primary Recommendation:

**Lucide**

---

# 11.4 Stroke Rules

Desktop

2px

Mobile

1.75px

Never mix stroke widths.

Every icon should appear visually balanced regardless of size.

---

# 11.5 Corner Geometry

Corners should be:

Rounded.

Soft.

Friendly.

Avoid geometric perfection.

Human-made objects feel more trustworthy than mathematically perfect objects.

---

# 11.6 Icon Sizes

Extra Small

16px

Small

20px

Default

24px

Large

32px

Hero

48px

Decorative

64px

Avoid arbitrary sizing.

---

# 11.7 Icon Spacing

Icons never touch text.

Minimum spacing

12px

Preferred spacing

16px

Icon alignment should always follow the baseline of accompanying text.

---

# 11.8 Icon Colors

Default

Charcoal

Muted

Stone Gray

Hover

Champagne Gold

Disabled

Ash Gray

Success

Muted Green

Error

Muted Red

Icons should never become colorful illustrations.

---

# 11.9 Interactive Icons

Interactive icons should provide subtle feedback.

Allowed

Opacity

Color

Small scale (1.05x)

Tiny rotation (≤2° only when meaningful)

Forbidden

Bounce

Spin

Explosion

Elastic motion

Large scaling

Interaction should feel tactile.

Not playful.

---

# 11.10 Decorative Icons

Decorative icons should be rare.

Examples

Quote marks.

Tiny botanical separator.

Small sparkle.

Divider ornament.

Maximum size

24px

Decorative icons must never compete with content.

---

# 11.11 Navigation Icons

Navigation icons should prioritize clarity.

Examples

Home

Discover

Messages

Matches

Profile

Settings

Notifications

Every navigation icon should remain recognizable at 20px.

---

# 11.12 Action Icons

Common actions

Search

Filter

Bookmark

Share

Edit

Delete

Report

Block

Upload

Download

Verify

Every action icon should have an accessible text label where appropriate.

Never rely on icons alone.

---

# 11.13 Status Icons

Success

✓

Pending

Clock

Verified

Shield Check

Warning

Triangle

Error

Circle Alert

Premium

Sparkle or Crown (very restrained)

Avoid using stars for verification.

Verification should feel authoritative.

---

# 11.14 Profile Icons

Profile-related icons should communicate lifestyle rather than decoration.

Examples

Location

Education

Profession

Religion

Languages

Family

Children

Pets

Travel

Interests

Values

Icons should always support text.

Never replace it.

---

# 11.15 Communication Icons

Messages

Phone

Video

Voice

Attachment

Emoji

These should remain understated.

Messaging is about conversation,

not interface.

---

# 11.16 AI Icons

Avoid

Robot.

Brain.

Circuit.

Chip.

Magic wand.

Instead use

Compass.

Thread.

Constellation.

Light.

Connection.

Growth.

AI should feel like thoughtful guidance,

not machinery.

---

# 11.17 Verification Symbol

Verification is one of Vivah's most important trust signals.

Preferred

Shield with checkmark.

Not

Blue social media checkmarks.

The verification symbol should communicate safety,

not popularity.

---

# 11.18 Premium Symbol

Premium is represented through craftsmanship.

Preferred

Small champagne sparkle.

Minimal crown.

Elegant geometric mark.

Avoid

Large crowns.

Diamonds.

Coins.

Money icons.

Luxury should feel quiet.

---

# 11.19 Notification Symbol

Notifications should never feel alarming.

Default

Bell

Active

Bell with subtle indicator.

Avoid flashing badges.

Notification counts should remain understated.

---

# 11.20 Empty State Symbols

Instead of generic boxes,

use meaningful objects.

Example

No Messages

Envelope.

No Matches

Two threads not yet connected.

No Notifications

Small bell.

No Saved Profiles

Bookmark.

Every empty state should remain hopeful.

---

# 11.21 Symbol Language

Vivah avoids cliché relationship symbols.

Forbidden

Large Hearts

Cupid

Love Arrows

Broken Hearts

Wedding Rings

Kissing Couples

Allowed

Threads

Pathways

Doorways

Windows

Lanterns

Trees

Gardens

Leaves

Light

Books

Letters

Home

Conversation

Growth

These symbols communicate relationships more maturely.

---

# 11.22 Brand Symbols

The recurring symbols throughout Vivah should include:

Thread

Primary brand symbol.

Represents connection.

Doorway

Represents beginnings.

Garden Path

Represents journey.

Lantern

Represents guidance.

Window

Represents openness.

Tree

Represents growth.

Letter

Represents meaningful communication.

These motifs should subtly appear in illustrations, onboarding, and storytelling—not necessarily as UI icons.

---

# 11.23 Illustration vs Icon

Icons explain.

Illustrations inspire.

Never confuse them.

Icons remain functional.

Illustrations remain emotional.

---

# 11.24 Accessibility

Icons must never communicate meaning alone.

Every important icon requires:

Label

Tooltip

Supporting text

Or clear context.

Minimum touch target

44 × 44px

Keyboard focus must remain visible.

---

# 11.25 Icon Anti-Patterns

Reject

Emoji-style icons.

3D icons.

Gradient icons.

Filled icons mixed with outlined icons.

Multiple icon styles.

Overly detailed icons.

Animated icons everywhere.

Corporate enterprise icons.

Technology symbols for AI.

Visual inconsistency destroys trust.

---

# 11.26 Icon Tokens

```css
--icon-xs: 16px;

--icon-sm: 20px;

--icon-md: 24px;

--icon-lg: 32px;

--icon-xl: 48px;

--icon-color-default;

--icon-color-muted;

--icon-color-hover;

--icon-color-success;

--icon-color-warning;

--icon-color-error;

--icon-stroke-width;
```

No component may define icon sizes independently.

---

# 11.27 Review Checklist

Before approving iconography:

□ Does every icon improve understanding?

□ Is only one icon family used?

□ Are strokes consistent?

□ Are icons accessible?

□ Are icons secondary to content?

□ Are symbols mature rather than cliché?

□ Does AI avoid robotic symbolism?

□ Does verification communicate trust?

□ Could every icon still make sense without color?

If any answer is "No,"

revise the icon system.

---

# End of Chapter 11

Absolutely. In fact, I'd like to **raise the quality** from here.

The first 11 chapters established the philosophy. Now we're entering the chapters that will directly affect how Vivah looks and feels. I'll write them with the depth of an actual design system used by a professional product team.

---

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume II — Visual Language

# Chapter 12 — Photography & Imagery System

---

# 12.1 Philosophy

Photography is the emotional heartbeat of Vivah.

Before users trust technology, they trust people.

Photography exists to communicate authenticity.

Not perfection.

Not aspiration.

Not fantasy.

Every photograph should answer one silent question:

> **"Could this genuinely be someone's life?"**

If the answer is no,

the photograph should not be used.

Vivah never presents idealized romance.

Vivah presents believable human connection.

---

# 12.2 The Role of Photography

Photography has five responsibilities.

Establish trust.

↓

Create emotional connection.

↓

Provide cultural familiarity.

↓

Support storytelling.

↓

Humanize technology.

Photography should never exist merely to fill empty space.

Every image must communicate something meaningful.

---

# 12.3 Emotional Tone

Every photograph should evoke one or more of the following emotions.

Hope.

Comfort.

Belonging.

Respect.

Warmth.

Joy.

Calm.

Confidence.

Partnership.

Never

Urgency.

Excitement.

Luxury for its own sake.

Loneliness.

Perfection.

Fantasy.

---

# 12.4 Authenticity

The people shown should feel real.

They should resemble people users encounter in everyday life.

Different ages.

Different professions.

Different lifestyles.

Different personalities.

Different family structures.

Different regions.

Authenticity builds trust far more effectively than perfection.

---

# 12.5 Representation

Vivah should respectfully represent the diversity of the communities it serves.

Photography should include people with different:

Skin tones.

Professions.

Cities.

Educational backgrounds.

Family structures.

Aspirations.

Lifestyle choices.

Representation should feel natural.

Never forced.

Never tokenistic.

---

# 12.6 Lifestyle Over Romance

The platform is not selling weddings.

It is helping people imagine life together.

Therefore prioritize photography showing:

Morning tea.

Cooking together.

Walking in parks.

Reading books.

Travelling.

Visiting parents.

Working from home.

Laughing naturally.

Preparing meals.

Festival gatherings.

Weekend hobbies.

Conversations.

Relationships are built through shared moments.

Not cinematic poses.

---

# 12.7 Expressions

Preferred expressions

Natural smile.

Quiet happiness.

Comfortable eye contact.

Conversation.

Laughter.

Thoughtfulness.

Curiosity.

Avoid

Exaggerated smiles.

Fashion poses.

Perfect symmetry.

Magazine expressions.

Over-directed emotion.

People should appear relaxed.

---

# 12.8 Camera Angles

Preferred

Eye level.

Slightly above eye level.

Natural perspective.

Environmental framing.

Avoid

Extreme close-ups.

Extreme wide angles.

Drone shots.

Dutch angles.

Fashion editorial compositions.

Photography should feel like an observer.

Not a director.

---

# 12.9 Lighting

Preferred

Window light.

Morning light.

Golden hour.

Open shade.

Soft interior light.

Diffused daylight.

Avoid

Flash.

Harsh sunlight.

Nightclub lighting.

Artificial HDR.

Heavy color grading.

The image should feel naturally illuminated.

---

# 12.10 Color Grading

Photography should share a unified color language.

Characteristics

Warm.

Neutral.

Slightly desaturated.

Soft contrast.

Natural whites.

Muted greens.

Gentle gold.

Avoid

Oversaturated colors.

Instagram filters.

Cool blue edits.

Heavy orange tones.

High HDR processing.

Every photograph should appear timeless.

---

# 12.11 Depth of Field

Preferred

Moderate depth.

Soft background separation.

Readable subjects.

Avoid

Extremely blurred backgrounds.

Artificial portrait effects.

Heavy computational blur.

The environment should remain part of the story.

---

# 12.12 Background Selection

Backgrounds should support human stories.

Examples

Homes.

Libraries.

Gardens.

Courtyards.

Cafés.

Bookstores.

Parks.

Studios.

Mountains.

Architecture.

Avoid

Blank studio walls.

Wedding stages.

Luxury cars.

Private jets.

Artificial sets.

The background should tell part of the story.

---

# 12.13 Composition

Preferred compositions

Rule of thirds.

Negative space.

Architectural framing.

Natural leading lines.

Open environments.

Avoid

Crowded images.

Centered portraits everywhere.

Busy backgrounds.

Visual clutter.

Every photograph should breathe.

---

# 12.14 Family Photography

Families should appear genuine.

Examples

Cooking together.

Tea conversations.

Festival preparation.

Parents smiling naturally.

Shared meals.

Celebrating milestones.

Avoid

Formal family portraits.

Everyone looking directly at camera.

Artificial posing.

Families should feel lived-in.

---

# 12.15 Couple Photography

Avoid obvious romance.

Preferred

Conversation.

Walking.

Reading together.

Travelling.

Cooking.

Laughing.

Shared hobbies.

Looking at scenery.

Quiet companionship.

Avoid

Forehead touching.

Heart poses.

Holding roses.

Forced intimacy.

Cinematic wedding shoots.

The relationship should feel authentic.

---

# 12.16 Individual Portraits

Profile photography should communicate personality.

Users should be encouraged to upload photographs showing

Travel.

Profession.

Reading.

Sports.

Music.

Cooking.

Pets.

Art.

Community.

Rather than only posed portraits.

---

# 12.17 Environmental Storytelling

Objects often communicate personality more effectively than expressions.

Examples

Books.

Plants.

Sketchbooks.

Musical instruments.

Travel bags.

Tea cups.

Cameras.

Paint brushes.

Running shoes.

Maps.

Letters.

Use environments to tell stories.

---

# 12.18 Cropping Rules

Never crop:

Foreheads.

Hands during gestures.

Important contextual objects.

Maintain generous breathing room.

Portraits should feel comfortable.

Not compressed.

---

# 12.19 Photography Hierarchy

The largest photograph on a page should represent the page's emotional purpose.

Secondary images provide supporting context.

No page should contain multiple competing hero photographs.

---

# 12.20 Image Treatments

Allowed

Soft fade.

Subtle vignette.

Warm overlay (≤5%).

Very light paper grain.

Forbidden

Heavy blur.

Glow.

Gradient overlays.

Colored filters.

Glass overlays.

Lens effects.

Photography should remain honest.

---

# 12.21 Motion

Photography may contain subtle movement.

Examples

Slow zoom.

Ambient parallax.

Tiny environmental movement.

Soft fade transitions.

Never

Fast slideshow.

Carousel autoplay.

Ken Burns exaggeration.

Motion should remain invisible.

---

# 12.22 AI Generated Images

If AI-generated imagery is used,

it must satisfy the same quality standards as real photography.

Avoid

Plastic skin.

Perfect faces.

Artificial smiles.

Unnatural fingers.

Fantasy architecture.

Impossible lighting.

If an AI image appears artificial,

it must not be used.

Authenticity always wins.

---

# 12.23 Illustration vs Photography

Photography communicates

Reality.

Illustrations communicate

Ideas.

Never replace meaningful photography with illustrations.

Illustrations should complement.

Not substitute.

---

# 12.24 Accessibility

Every photograph requires meaningful alternative text.

Decorative images should be ignored by assistive technologies.

Essential imagery must never be the sole method of communicating information.

---

# 12.25 Anti-Patterns

Reject immediately

Wedding stage photography.

Stock couples staring at the camera.

Business handshake imagery.

Corporate office stock photos.

People holding coffee while laughing at laptops.

Luxury fashion poses.

Drone wedding shots.

Perfect Instagram aesthetics.

Artificial romance.

Visible watermark photography.

Anything that feels staged rather than lived.

---

# 12.26 Photography Asset Library

The Vivah asset library should be categorized by moments, not subjects.

Morning Routines

Family Moments

Conversations

Travel

Reading

Cooking

Celebrations

Festivals

Work

Nature

Home

Community

Pets

Rather than

Men

Women

Couples

Families

This reinforces storytelling throughout the product.

---

# 12.27 Photography Review Checklist

Before approving any image:

□ Does this image feel authentic?

□ Could this genuinely be someone's real life?

□ Does it communicate warmth?

□ Is the lighting natural?

□ Is the composition calm?

□ Does it support trust?

□ Does it avoid stereotypes?

□ Does it tell a story without words?

□ Would this image still feel timeless ten years from now?

□ Is it supporting the interface rather than competing with it?

If any answer is "No,"

the photograph should be replaced.

---

# 12.28 Final Principle

Photography is not used to make Vivah beautiful.

Photography is used to make Vivah believable.

When users trust the people they see,

they begin trusting the platform itself.

---

# End of Chapter 12

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume III — Motion & Interaction

# Chapter 13 — Motion Language & Choreography

---

# 13.1 Philosophy

Motion is not animation.

Motion is communication.

Every movement inside Vivah must answer one question:

**"Why is this moving?"**

If there is no meaningful answer,

the motion should not exist.

Users should rarely notice animations.

Instead, they should simply feel that the interface behaves naturally.

The greatest compliment is not

> "That animation is amazing."

It is

> "Everything feels effortless."

---

# 13.2 Motion Objectives

Motion exists to accomplish five goals.

Guide Attention

↓

Maintain Context

↓

Provide Feedback

↓

Reduce Cognitive Load

↓

Create Emotional Comfort

Motion never exists to entertain.

Motion never exists to show technical capability.

---

# 13.3 Motion Personality

Vivah moves like a thoughtful host.

Never hurried.

Never delayed.

Never dramatic.

The movement should feel:

Elegant.

Gentle.

Confident.

Organic.

Refined.

Patient.

Purposeful.

Avoid movement that feels:

Playful.

Aggressive.

Mechanical.

Elastic.

Chaotic.

Gamified.

---

# 13.4 Motion Hierarchy

Not every animation deserves equal attention.

Motion should follow this hierarchy.

Level 1

Micro Feedback

↓

Level 2

Component Transition

↓

Level 3

Page Transition

↓

Level 4

Environmental Motion

↓

Level 5

Celebration Motion

Higher levels occur less frequently.

---

# 13.5 Environmental Motion

The environment should always feel alive.

Almost imperceptibly.

Allowed

Changing sunlight.

Soft drifting shadows.

Curtains reacting gently.

Leaves moving.

Floating dust.

Ambient reflections.

Forbidden

Moving backgrounds.

Constant floating objects.

Flying decorations.

Heavy particles.

Rotating ornaments.

The environment breathes.

It never performs.

---

# 13.6 User Motion

User-triggered interactions always take priority over environmental motion.

Whenever the user interacts,

background motion should visually "step back."

The interface should respond to the user.

Not compete with them.

---

# 13.7 Timing Philosophy

Motion should feel physically believable.

Recommended durations

Tiny Feedback

100–150ms

Hover

150–200ms

Cards

200–250ms

Dialogs

250–300ms

Page Transition

400–600ms

Environmental

20–60 seconds

Never create animations longer than necessary.

Waiting should never become part of the experience.

---

# 13.8 Easing

Vivah uses natural easing.

Preferred

Ease Out

Ease In-Out

Spring (soft)

Forbidden

Linear

Bounce

Elastic

Overshoot

Back

Cartoon easing

Motion should end gently.

Never snap.

---

# 13.9 Entrance Motion

New elements should enter naturally.

Preferred

Fade

Rise

Slight Scale

Opacity

Soft Blur

Maximum movement

24px

Never allow components to fly across the screen.

---

# 13.10 Exit Motion

Objects should leave respectfully.

Fade.

Shrink slightly.

Reduce opacity.

Slide minimally.

Never disappear instantly.

Never explode.

Never spin away.

---

# 13.11 Hover Philosophy

Hover communicates availability.

Not excitement.

Allowed

Shadow increase.

Slight elevation.

Color refinement.

Border highlight.

Tiny scale (≤1.02).

Forbidden

Large scaling.

Glow.

Rotation.

Bounce.

Hover should feel tactile.

---

# 13.12 Button Motion

Buttons respond immediately.

Sequence

Hover

↓

Press

↓

Release

↓

Confirmation

Button presses should feel physical.

Not digital.

The user should feel they pressed something.

---

# 13.13 Card Motion

Cards should respond as objects.

Hover

Small elevation.

Tiny shadow increase.

Border refinement.

Optional

1–2° perspective shift.

Nothing more.

Cards never float dramatically.

---

# 13.14 Navigation Motion

Navigation should remain stable.

Scrolling

Smooth appearance.

Hover

Simple highlight.

Active state

Elegant underline.

Never animate navigation excessively.

Navigation represents stability.

---

# 13.15 Scroll Motion

Scrolling should resemble walking through spaces.

Not flipping slides.

Every section introduces one new concept.

Transitions should overlap gently.

Avoid abrupt scene changes.

---

# 13.16 Progressive Reveal

Content should reveal itself progressively.

Preferred sequence

Headline

↓

Supporting Text

↓

Illustration

↓

Primary CTA

↓

Secondary Elements

This creates reading rhythm.

---

# 13.17 Loading Motion

Loading should reassure.

Preferred

Skeletons.

Soft shimmer.

Progress indicators.

Meaningful placeholders.

Avoid

Infinite spinners.

Flashy loaders.

Complex loading scenes.

Users should always know the system is working.

---

# 13.18 Success Motion

Success deserves recognition.

Not celebration.

Examples

Checkmark draw.

Soft glow.

Gentle expansion.

Brief color transition.

Avoid

Confetti.

Fireworks.

Explosions.

Users completed a task.

They did not win a game.

---

# 13.19 Error Motion

Errors should educate.

Not punish.

Examples

Tiny horizontal shift.

Soft color change.

Helpful explanation.

Avoid

Violent shaking.

Flashing red.

Loud animations.

The interface remains calm.

Even during mistakes.

---

# 13.20 Modal Motion

Dialogs emerge from the current context.

Never appear from nowhere.

Preferred

Background softens.

Dialog rises slightly.

Focus transfers naturally.

Closing returns attention.

The user should never lose orientation.

---

# 13.21 Form Motion

Forms should guide completion.

Focused field

↓

Validation

↓

Confirmation

↓

Next field

Avoid overwhelming users with simultaneous animations.

---

# 13.22 Notification Motion

Notifications should arrive quietly.

Slide.

Fade.

Small elevation.

Disappear naturally.

Never interrupt primary work.

---

# 13.23 Motion Density

No more than three independent animations should occur simultaneously within the viewport.

If more than three are visible,

reduce motion.

Luxury values restraint.

---

# 13.24 Motion and Performance

All motion must remain GPU accelerated.

Preferred properties

Transform.

Opacity.

Filter (minimal).

Avoid animating

Width.

Height.

Top.

Left.

Box-shadow continuously.

Layout properties.

Motion should never reduce responsiveness.

---

# 13.25 Reduced Motion

Vivah fully respects user preferences.

When reduced motion is enabled

Remove environmental movement.

Replace transitions with fades.

Remove decorative animation.

Preserve usability.

Accessibility overrides aesthetics.

---

# 13.26 Motion Rhythm

Every screen should establish rhythm.

Interaction.

↓

Pause.

↓

Interaction.

↓

Pause.

↓

Transition.

Avoid constant movement.

Stillness increases perceived quality.

---

# 13.27 Choreography

Multiple components should move together.

Never randomly.

Example

Heading

↓

Image

↓

CTA

↓

Supporting content

Everything enters with intention.

Like musicians following the same conductor.

---

# 13.28 Emotional Motion

Every animation should reinforce one emotion.

Welcome.

Comfort.

Discovery.

Understanding.

Confirmation.

Hope.

If an animation cannot be assigned one of these emotions,

remove it.

---

# 13.29 Motion Anti-Patterns

Reject immediately

Bounce.

Elastic.

Rubber band.

Spinning cards.

Rotating buttons.

Parallax overload.

Continuous floating.

Particle storms.

Confetti.

Fireworks.

Gaming effects.

Attention-seeking motion.

Motion that delays interaction.

Motion that blocks interaction.

Motion that exists only because it "looks cool."

---

# 13.30 Motion Tokens

```css
--duration-instant: 100ms;

--duration-fast: 150ms;

--duration-normal: 250ms;

--duration-slow: 400ms;

--duration-page: 600ms;

--ease-standard;

--ease-soft;

--ease-enter;

--ease-exit;

--motion-hover-scale;

--motion-card-elevation;

--motion-dialog-offset;
```

Every component must use shared motion tokens.

No custom durations.

No arbitrary easing.

---

# 13.31 Motion Review Checklist

Before approving any interaction

□ Does every animation have a purpose?

□ Does motion improve understanding?

□ Is movement physically believable?

□ Does the animation finish quickly?

□ Does it respect reduced-motion preferences?

□ Is performance preserved?

□ Does the interface remain calm?

□ Is there unnecessary movement?

□ Does motion support trust?

□ Would the interface still feel premium with half as much animation?

If the answer to the last question is "No,"

the motion system is too dependent on effects.

---

# 13.32 The Final Rule

The best motion is the motion users remember emotionally,

not visually.

Users should leave Vivah thinking

> "Everything felt smooth."

Never

> "Everything was animated."

---

# End of Chapter 13

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume III — Motion & Interaction

# Chapter 14 — Microinteractions & Emotional Feedback

---

# 14.1 Philosophy

Microinteractions are the moments that make Vivah feel human.

They are not animations.

They are conversations between the interface and the user.

Every click.

Every hover.

Every validation.

Every confirmation.

Every transition.

These tiny moments collectively define how trustworthy the product feels.

The user should never consciously admire them.

They should simply feel understood.

---

# 14.2 Purpose

Every microinteraction must achieve at least one of the following:

Provide feedback.

↓

Reduce uncertainty.

↓

Guide the next action.

↓

Reinforce trust.

↓

Reward completion.

If it does none of these,

it should not exist.

---

# 14.3 The Four Stages

Every interaction follows four emotional stages.

**Anticipation**

↓

**Action**

↓

**Response**

↓

**Resolution**

No interaction should stop halfway.

Every action deserves closure.

---

# 14.4 Cursor Language

The cursor is the user's first conversation with the interface.

Rules

Clickable elements respond immediately.

Disabled elements clearly communicate inactivity.

Interactive cards subtly acknowledge presence.

Never surprise the user.

Cursor feedback should always be immediate.

---

# 14.5 Hover States

Hover should communicate

"I am available."

Not

"Look at me."

Allowed changes

Opacity

Border refinement

Shadow refinement

Tiny elevation

Very small scale (1.01–1.02)

Gentle light shift

Forbidden

Rotation

Glow

Large scaling

Bounce

Color explosions

Hover should remain elegant.

---

# 14.6 Press States

Buttons should feel physical.

Sequence

Finger touches

↓

Surface compresses slightly

↓

Shadow softens

↓

Color deepens

↓

Action executes

↓

Button returns naturally

The user should subconsciously perceive resistance.

---

# 14.7 Focus States

Focus communicates confidence.

Preferred

Warm champagne outline.

Soft shadow.

Subtle elevation.

Visible but elegant.

Never remove focus outlines.

Keyboard users deserve the same premium experience.

---

# 14.8 Form Validation

Validation should encourage.

Never criticize.

Incorrect

❌ Invalid Name

Preferred

✓ Please enter your full name.

Incorrect

❌ Wrong Password

Preferred

✓ That password doesn't match our records.

Try again.

Language reduces anxiety.

---

# 14.9 Input Behaviour

Inputs should respond gradually.

Empty

↓

Hover

↓

Focused

↓

Typing

↓

Validated

↓

Completed

Each stage should feel connected.

Avoid abrupt transitions.

---

# 14.10 Successful Actions

Every successful action deserves acknowledgement.

Examples

Bookmark saved.

Profile updated.

Message delivered.

Payment completed.

Verification submitted.

Feedback

Small checkmark.

Gentle color transition.

Soft confirmation message.

Never interrupt workflow.

---

# 14.11 Error Behaviour

Errors should teach.

Not punish.

Sequence

Highlight field.

↓

Explain issue.

↓

Suggest correction.

↓

Return focus.

Never

Shake violently.

Flash red.

Display technical language.

---

# 14.12 Loading Feedback

Waiting creates anxiety.

Always communicate progress.

Examples

Skeleton layout.

Button loading.

Image placeholder.

Message placeholder.

Profile placeholder.

Users should always know the system is working.

---

# 14.13 Progressive Completion

Long processes should celebrate progress.

Examples

Profile Completion

15%

↓

40%

↓

75%

↓

100%

Every milestone deserves subtle encouragement.

Never guilt users for incomplete profiles.

---

# 14.14 Toggle Behaviour

Toggles should imitate physical switches.

Movement

Short.

Purposeful.

Immediate.

State should always be obvious.

---

# 14.15 Checkbox Behaviour

Checkboxes represent certainty.

Animation

Outline

↓

Fill

↓

Checkmark

Duration

150ms

No bounce.

No flourish.

---

# 14.16 Radio Buttons

Radio buttons should clearly indicate exclusivity.

Selection should feel calm.

Not competitive.

Transition

Border

↓

Fill

↓

Center indicator

---

# 14.17 Sliders

Sliders should feel tactile.

Handle follows pointer naturally.

Movement remains precise.

Values update continuously.

Never lag.

---

# 14.18 Dropdowns

Dropdowns emerge naturally.

Sequence

Click

↓

Expand

↓

Focus

↓

Selection

↓

Collapse

Never teleport.

Never fade without movement.

---

# 14.19 Search

Search should encourage exploration.

Focus

↓

Placeholder fades

↓

Typing begins

↓

Suggestions appear

↓

Selection

↓

Results

Every transition should feel instantaneous.

---

# 14.20 Profile Cards

When hovering over profiles

Increase depth slightly.

Reveal additional information.

Never dramatically transform the card.

The person remains the focus.

---

# 14.21 Save Interaction

Saving should feel reassuring.

Bookmark

↓

Fill

↓

Confirmation

↓

Return to resting state

Avoid persistent animations.

---

# 14.22 Message Sending

Messages should communicate reliability.

User types

↓

Send

↓

Bubble appears

↓

Delivered

↓

Read

Every state transition should remain subtle.

---

# 14.23 Notifications

Arrival

Gentle slide.

↓

Visible

↓

Pause

↓

Fade

Users should never feel interrupted.

---

# 14.24 Image Loading

Images should never suddenly appear.

Preferred

Blur-up.

Opacity.

Soft fade.

Never

Flash.

Pop.

Scale dramatically.

---

# 14.25 Scrolling Feedback

Scrolling should reveal progress naturally.

Avoid sticky elements competing for attention.

Navigation may gently adapt.

Nothing should jump unexpectedly.

---

# 14.26 Empty States

Empty states should encourage action.

Never disappointment.

Instead of

"No Matches."

Prefer

"Your journey has just begun.

Let's help you discover meaningful connections."

Every empty state should create hope.

---

# 14.27 Achievement Moments

Vivah rarely celebrates.

When it does,

it celebrates quietly.

Examples

Profile verified.

First conversation.

Profile completed.

Membership activated.

Visual language

Light.

Warmth.

Small illustration.

Gentle motion.

Never confetti.

---

# 14.28 Recovery

Undo should exist wherever practical.

Deleting.

Unsaving.

Archiving.

Blocking.

Users should feel safe making mistakes.

---

# 14.29 Emotional Consistency

Every interaction should leave the user feeling

Respected.

Guided.

Confident.

Supported.

Never

Pressured.

Judged.

Confused.

Overwhelmed.

---

# 14.30 Timing Harmony

Interactions should share timing.

Hover

≈150ms

Validation

≈200ms

Success

≈250ms

Dialogs

≈300ms

Consistency creates subconscious confidence.

---

# 14.31 Sound

Vivah is designed to function silently.

No interface sounds.

No clicks.

No notification chimes.

No success sounds.

Silence respects users.

Future accessibility options may optionally introduce sound.

---

# 14.32 Haptics

Mobile devices may use gentle haptic feedback.

Allowed

Successful save.

Successful payment.

Profile verification.

Message sent.

Avoid

Continuous vibration.

Heavy haptics.

Game-like feedback.

---

# 14.33 Emotional Scale

Every interaction should score high in

Clarity.

Comfort.

Predictability.

Warmth.

Respect.

And low in

Surprise.

Urgency.

Excitement.

Drama.

---

# 14.34 Anti-Patterns

Reject immediately

Hover explosions.

Button morphing.

Elastic inputs.

Shaking dialogs.

Aggressive validation.

Floating buttons.

Auto-opening panels.

Unexpected modals.

Forced onboarding.

Gamification.

Attention-seeking interactions.

Microinteractions should disappear into the experience.

---

# 14.35 Design Tokens

```css
--hover-duration

--press-duration

--focus-duration

--validation-duration

--success-duration

--loading-duration

--hover-shadow

--hover-scale

--press-scale

--focus-ring

--success-color

--error-color

--warning-color
```

Every interaction must use shared tokens.

---

# 14.36 Review Checklist

Before approving any interaction

□ Does the user receive immediate feedback?

□ Does the interaction reduce uncertainty?

□ Is the motion subtle?

□ Is the language encouraging?

□ Is accessibility preserved?

□ Does the interaction finish naturally?

□ Is there an opportunity to undo destructive actions?

□ Does the interaction feel human?

□ Does it reduce anxiety?

□ Would this still feel premium if the animation duration were cut in half?

If any answer is "No,"

the microinteraction requires refinement.

---

# 14.37 Final Principle

A beautiful interface is remembered.

A thoughtful interface is trusted.

Vivah should strive for trust above admiration.

Every microinteraction is an opportunity to quietly reassure the user that they are in the right place.

---

# End of Chapter 14

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume III — Motion & Interaction

# Chapter 15 — Scroll Experience & Narrative Flow

---

# 15.1 Philosophy

Scrolling is not navigation.

Scrolling is storytelling.

Every scroll should feel like walking through a carefully designed physical space.

Users should never feel like they are moving through disconnected sections.

Instead,

they should experience one continuous journey.

The page should unfold naturally,

revealing new ideas only when the user is ready.

---

# 15.2 Narrative Structure

Every long page follows the same storytelling rhythm.

Welcome

↓

Curiosity

↓

Understanding

↓

Confidence

↓

Connection

↓

Action

↓

Reflection

↓

Completion

No section should interrupt this emotional progression.

---

# 15.3 Scroll Pace

Vivah values deliberate pacing.

The interface should never feel rushed.

Users should feel invited to continue.

Not pushed.

Scrolling should resemble walking through

a quiet museum,

a botanical garden,

or a thoughtfully designed home.

Never an infinite social feed.

---

# 15.4 Viewport Rule

Every viewport should communicate exactly one primary idea.

Examples

Hero

↓

Mission

↓

Profiles

↓

Success Stories

↓

Trust

↓

Call To Action

Never introduce multiple competing messages within the same viewport.

---

# 15.5 Section Identity

Each section should feel unique.

Not through different layouts.

But through

Light.

Spacing.

Photography.

Illustration.

Content.

Material.

Motion.

Users should always know they have entered a new chapter.

Without feeling they left the product.

---

# 15.6 Scroll Hierarchy

Every section should follow this order.

Section Marker

↓

Headline

↓

Supporting Copy

↓

Visual

↓

Primary Action

↓

Transition

Consistency allows users to predict the interface.

Prediction builds confidence.

---

# 15.7 Scroll Rhythm

Alternating rhythm creates comfort.

Example

Visual Left

↓

Visual Right

↓

Centered Story

↓

Grid

↓

Full Width

↓

Editorial Layout

↓

CTA

Avoid repeating identical layouts continuously.

Variation should remain controlled.

---

# 15.8 Entry Transitions

Sections should appear before they become active.

Preferred

Fade.

Rise.

Opacity.

Small translation.

Maximum movement

32px.

Users should never feel content suddenly appears.

---

# 15.9 Exit Transitions

Sections should leave gracefully.

Opacity decreases.

Motion softens.

The next section begins appearing before the previous fully disappears.

This overlap creates continuity.

---

# 15.10 Hero Scroll

The Hero introduces the journey.

As users scroll,

the Hero should slowly surrender attention.

Headline remains readable.

Background shifts subtly.

Lighting changes naturally.

Nothing dramatic occurs.

The user simply continues forward.

---

# 15.11 Reading Behaviour

Most users scan before reading.

Therefore,

each section should communicate its purpose within three seconds.

Use

Clear headings.

Meaningful imagery.

Generous spacing.

Short supporting paragraphs.

---

# 15.12 Visual Anchors

Every major section contains one visual anchor.

Examples

Portrait.

Illustration.

Architecture.

Quote.

Profile.

Story.

Visual anchors guide attention naturally.

Never use multiple competing anchors.

---

# 15.13 Layer Progression

Scroll should gradually reveal depth.

Beginning

Open.

Bright.

Simple.

Middle

Richer information.

Greater interaction.

Ending

Reflection.

Confidence.

Invitation.

Never reveal maximum complexity immediately.

---

# 15.14 Momentum

Scrolling should preserve momentum.

Avoid

Sudden stopping.

Unexpected carousels.

Scroll hijacking.

Forced animations.

Users remain in control.

Always.

---

# 15.15 Long Pages

Long pages should feel shorter.

Methods

Meaningful rhythm.

Alternating compositions.

Storytelling.

Visual resets.

Comfortable spacing.

Never compress content simply to reduce page length.

---

# 15.16 Transitional Spaces

Every transition deserves breathing room.

Whitespace acts as a hallway between rooms.

Transitions should never feel abrupt.

Examples

Soft gradient.

Quote.

Illustration.

Ambient light.

Botanical divider.

These moments allow users to mentally reset.

---

# 15.17 Visual Resets

Every three to four sections,

introduce a slower moment.

Examples

Editorial quote.

Single photograph.

Minimal illustration.

Personal story.

This prevents visual fatigue.

---

# 15.18 Scroll Velocity

Design must remain beautiful regardless of scrolling speed.

Whether users scroll quickly or slowly,

the experience should remain coherent.

Never rely on users moving at a specific speed.

---

# 15.19 Sticky Elements

Sticky elements should remain minimal.

Allowed

Navigation.

Progress indicator.

Contextual filter.

Forbidden

Persistent banners.

Sticky advertisements.

Floating promotions.

Competing sticky panels.

The screen belongs to the content.

---

# 15.20 Horizontal Motion

Horizontal movement should be rare.

Allowed

Image galleries.

Profile comparisons.

Timelines.

Forbidden

Entire page transitions.

Horizontal storytelling.

Unexpected sideways movement.

Vertical scrolling remains primary.

---

# 15.21 Parallax

Parallax should remain almost invisible.

Maximum movement

10–20px.

Purpose

Depth.

Not spectacle.

If users notice parallax,

it is probably excessive.

---

# 15.22 Progress Indicators

Users should always know where they are.

Examples

Section markers.

Timeline.

Step indicators.

Subtle navigation highlights.

Avoid

Large progress bars dominating the screen.

---

# 15.23 Narrative Sequencing

Information should unfold naturally.

Never explain everything immediately.

Example

Who we are

↓

How we help

↓

Why trust us

↓

Meet people

↓

Success stories

↓

Join Vivah

Every section answers a question created by the previous one.

---

# 15.24 Scroll Memory

Users returning to the page should immediately regain orientation.

Provide

Consistent landmarks.

Recognizable sections.

Stable navigation.

Predictable structure.

Never randomize layouts.

---

# 15.25 Interactive Moments

Interactive moments should interrupt scrolling only when valuable.

Examples

Profile preview.

Compatibility calculator.

Story reveal.

Values exploration.

Avoid interactions that block progress.

---

# 15.26 Performance

Scroll performance is sacred.

Target

60 FPS.

Never sacrifice smoothness for visual effects.

Prefer

Transform.

Opacity.

CSS variables.

Avoid

Heavy JavaScript.

Continuous layout recalculation.

Expensive filters.

Large canvas scenes.

The smoothness of scrolling contributes more to perceived quality than complex animations.

---

# 15.27 Mobile Scroll

Mobile receives special consideration.

Thumb zones.

Natural momentum.

Comfortable spacing.

No tiny interactive targets.

One-handed operation should remain comfortable.

---

# 15.28 Accessibility

Scrolling should never hide information.

Respect

Reduced motion.

Keyboard navigation.

Screen readers.

Anchor links.

Focus order.

Users must remain in control.

---

# 15.29 Scroll Anti-Patterns

Reject

Scroll hijacking.

Forced snap scrolling.

Long pinned sections.

Storytelling that traps users.

Unexpected horizontal movement.

Continuous animations tied to scroll.

Large video backgrounds.

Overly cinematic experiences.

Infinite decorative effects.

Users came to find meaningful relationships,

not to watch a presentation.

---

# 15.30 Scroll Tokens

```css
--section-gap-sm: 80px;

--section-gap-md: 120px;

--section-gap-lg: 180px;

--scroll-reveal-offset: 24px;

--scroll-parallax-depth: 12px;

--transition-duration-section: 400ms;

--transition-ease-section: var(--ease-soft);

--max-content-width: 1440px;

--reading-width: 680px;
```

All page layouts should consume these shared tokens.

---

# 15.31 Homepage Narrative Blueprint

The homepage should follow this exact emotional sequence.

```text
Arrival
│
▼
A Place of Calm
│
▼
Why Vivah Exists
│
▼
How We Help
│
▼
Meet Genuine People
│
▼
Families & Values
│
▼
Stories of New Beginnings
│
▼
Trust & Verification
│
▼
Your Journey Starts Here
│
▼
Footer
```

Every section should naturally invite the next.

No abrupt changes in tone.

No disconnected blocks.

The homepage should feel like reading a beautifully designed story.

---

# 15.32 Final Principle

A visitor should never remember

how they scrolled.

They should remember

how the journey made them feel.

The highest compliment is not

> "The scrolling was impressive."

It is

> "The experience flowed naturally."

---

# End of Chapter 15

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume III — Motion & Interaction

# Chapter 16 — Accessibility & Inclusive Experience

---

# 16.1 Philosophy

Accessibility is not a compliance checklist.

Accessibility is respect.

Vivah exists to help people through one of the most meaningful decisions of their lives.

No person should feel excluded because of age, ability, technology, or circumstance.

Accessibility is therefore considered a core quality attribute of the product, equal in importance to usability, security, and performance.

Every feature must be designed for everyone before it is designed for anyone.

---

# 16.2 Design Principle

The interface should never assume that users:

Have perfect vision.

Have perfect hearing.

Use a mouse.

Use a keyboard.

Use the latest device.

Have fast internet.

Understand technology.

Can perceive color differences.

Accessibility begins by removing assumptions.

---

# 16.3 Inclusive Audience

Vivah serves multiple generations.

Young professionals.

Parents.

Grandparents.

Users with temporary injuries.

Users with permanent disabilities.

Users in bright sunlight.

Users using old mobile devices.

Users on unstable internet.

Every one of these situations deserves equal consideration.

---

# 16.4 Accessibility Standards

Minimum target

WCAG 2.2 AA

Preferred

WCAG AAA wherever practical.

Compliance is considered the minimum.

Usability remains the real objective.

---

# 16.5 Readability

Text should never become difficult to read.

Requirements

Minimum body size

16px preferred.

14px minimum.

Maximum paragraph width

70 characters.

Comfortable line height.

High contrast.

No justified paragraphs.

Readable typography is one of the strongest trust signals.

---

# 16.6 Color Independence

Color must never be the only method of communication.

Incorrect

Green means success.

Red means error.

Correct

Color

*

Icon

*

Text

*

Context

Every important state must remain understandable in grayscale.

---

# 16.7 Contrast

Minimum contrast

WCAG AA.

Preferred

7:1

Decorative backgrounds must never reduce readability.

Typography always wins over aesthetics.

---

# 16.8 Keyboard Navigation

Every interactive element must be reachable using only the keyboard.

Navigation order must remain logical.

Focus must never become trapped.

Escape should close overlays.

Enter should confirm actions where appropriate.

Space should activate controls.

Users should never need a mouse.

---

# 16.9 Focus Visibility

Keyboard focus must remain visible.

Focus indicators should feel premium.

Preferred

Warm champagne outline.

Soft shadow.

Subtle elevation.

Never remove browser focus styles without replacing them with something better.

---

# 16.10 Screen Readers

Every meaningful component must expose semantic information.

Buttons.

Links.

Inputs.

Images.

Dialogs.

Menus.

Navigation.

Progress indicators.

Decorative elements should remain hidden from assistive technologies.

---

# 16.11 Images

Every meaningful image requires descriptive alternative text.

Descriptions should explain purpose.

Not appearance.

Incorrect

"A smiling man."

Correct

"Profile photograph of Rajesh standing in a garden."

Decorative imagery should use empty alt text.

---

# 16.12 Motion Preferences

Respect

prefers-reduced-motion

Immediately.

Remove

Environmental animation.

Parallax.

Floating elements.

Decorative transitions.

Retain

Essential feedback.

Focus movement.

Navigation transitions.

Usability should remain unchanged.

---

# 16.13 Interaction Targets

Every interactive element must satisfy minimum touch size.

Minimum

44 × 44px

Preferred

48 × 48px

Users should never struggle to activate controls.

---

# 16.14 Forms

Forms should guide rather than challenge.

Every input requires

Visible label.

Placeholder (optional).

Helper text.

Error explanation.

Validation.

Focus indication.

Never rely on placeholders as labels.

---

# 16.15 Error Messages

Errors should explain

What happened.

Why it happened.

How to fix it.

Example

Incorrect

"Invalid input."

Preferred

"Please enter a valid email address so we can contact you."

---

# 16.16 Success Messages

Confirmation should be explicit.

Examples

"Profile saved."

"Photo uploaded."

"Verification submitted."

Users should never wonder whether their action succeeded.

---

# 16.17 Language

Write using plain language.

Avoid technical terminology.

Avoid internal system messages.

Avoid abbreviations unless universally understood.

Every sentence should feel respectful.

---

# 16.18 Cognitive Accessibility

Reduce mental effort.

Break complex processes into steps.

Use predictable layouts.

Maintain consistent terminology.

Avoid unnecessary choices.

Reduce memory load.

The interface should think,

so the user doesn't have to.

---

# 16.19 Reading Order

Screen readers and visual layouts should follow the same logical order.

Headings.

↓

Supporting text.

↓

Primary action.

↓

Secondary content.

Never create conflicting reading sequences.

---

# 16.20 Navigation

Navigation should remain predictable.

Primary navigation should never move unexpectedly.

Users should always know

Where they are.

How they arrived.

How to return.

Orientation reduces anxiety.

---

# 16.21 Dialogs

Dialogs should:

Receive focus immediately.

Trap focus while open.

Return focus after closing.

Support Escape.

Remain keyboard accessible.

Never leave users stranded.

---

# 16.22 Notifications

Notifications should not interrupt screen readers unnecessarily.

Critical messages

Announce immediately.

Informational messages

Announce politely.

Avoid excessive announcements.

---

# 16.23 Authentication

Authentication should remain accessible.

Password visibility toggle.

Clear requirements.

Helpful validation.

Accessible CAPTCHA alternatives.

OTP inputs supporting paste.

Auto-focus without trapping users.

---

# 16.24 Profile Cards

Profile cards should remain understandable without images.

Every important detail must remain available through text.

Images support.

They do not replace information.

---

# 16.25 Tables

Avoid tables on mobile whenever possible.

When required

Responsive layout.

Clear headers.

Logical reading order.

Screen reader support.

---

# 16.26 Charts

Charts should never communicate information visually alone.

Provide

Labels.

Summaries.

Descriptions.

Alternative formats.

---

# 16.27 Time Limits

Never introduce unnecessary countdowns.

Where timeouts exist

Warn users.

Allow extension.

Preserve progress.

Marriage decisions should never feel rushed.

---

# 16.28 Mobile Accessibility

Design for

One-handed use.

Large touch targets.

Visible typography.

Comfortable spacing.

Landscape support.

Dynamic text scaling.

Older devices.

---

# 16.29 Performance Accessibility

Fast interfaces are accessible interfaces.

Target

First meaningful interaction

<2 seconds.

Input latency

<100ms.

Scrolling

60 FPS.

Accessibility includes responsiveness.

---

# 16.30 Network Conditions

Support

Slow 3G.

Offline interruptions.

Temporary failures.

Retry actions.

Graceful degradation.

Users should never lose important information.

---

# 16.31 Emotional Accessibility

Accessibility includes emotional experience.

Avoid

Judgmental language.

Blame.

Pressure.

Urgency.

Embarrassment.

Prefer

Encouragement.

Guidance.

Patience.

Support.

Respect.

---

# 16.32 Internationalization

All interface components must support

Longer text.

Right-to-left layouts.

Unicode.

Variable font rendering.

Different date formats.

Different number systems.

Future localization must never require redesign.

---

# 16.33 Accessibility Testing

Every release should include

Keyboard testing.

Screen reader testing.

Color blindness testing.

Contrast verification.

Zoom testing.

Reduced motion testing.

Touch testing.

Responsive testing.

Accessibility is tested continuously.

Not once.

---

# 16.34 Accessibility Anti-Patterns

Reject immediately

Tiny buttons.

Placeholder-only forms.

Low contrast text.

Keyboard traps.

Hover-only interactions.

Color-only status indicators.

Autoplay media.

Unexpected focus changes.

Inaccessible modals.

Complex CAPTCHA.

Decorative text images.

Accessibility exceptions for aesthetics.

---

# 16.35 Accessibility Tokens

```css
--focus-ring-color;

--focus-ring-width;

--touch-target-min;

--contrast-high;

--contrast-medium;

--contrast-low;

--motion-enabled;

--motion-reduced;

--text-scale-small;

--text-scale-normal;

--text-scale-large;
```

Accessibility values must remain centralized.

Never hardcode accessibility behavior inside individual components.

---

# 16.36 Accessibility Review Checklist

Before approving any feature

□ Can every task be completed using only the keyboard?

□ Does every image have appropriate alternative text?

□ Is every state understandable without color?

□ Is typography readable at 200% zoom?

□ Does reduced motion preserve usability?

□ Are touch targets large enough?

□ Can screen readers understand the interface?

□ Is every error understandable?

□ Does the interface remain usable on slow devices?

□ Would a first-time user over the age of 60 feel comfortable using this screen?

If any answer is "No,"

the feature is not production-ready.

---

# 16.37 The Final Principle

Accessibility is not designing for edge cases.

It is designing for reality.

When Vivah becomes easier for someone with limited vision, slower internet, reduced mobility, or little technical experience,

it becomes a better product for everyone.

---

# End of Chapter 16

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume IV — Design System Components

# Chapter 17 — Component Philosophy & Design Tokens

---

# 17.1 Philosophy

Components are not reusable pieces of UI.

They are reusable expressions of the Vivah philosophy.

Every button.

Every card.

Every input.

Every modal.

Every badge.

Every menu.

Every interaction.

Must feel as though it belongs to the same carefully designed ecosystem.

Users should never feel that individual pages were designed by different people.

The design system exists to create visual consistency, engineering consistency, and emotional consistency.

---

# 17.2 The Atomic Philosophy

Vivah follows an atomic hierarchy.

```text
Design Tokens
        │
        ▼
Foundations
        │
        ▼
Atoms
        │
        ▼
Molecules
        │
        ▼
Organisms
        │
        ▼
Templates
        │
        ▼
Pages
```

No page should introduce unique visual rules.

Every page is assembled from the system.

Never designed independently.

---

# 17.3 Design Token Philosophy

Tokens are the single source of truth.

No developer should ever hardcode

Colors.

Spacing.

Radius.

Animation.

Typography.

Shadows.

Opacity.

Border width.

Anything that may change belongs inside tokens.

---

# 17.4 The Five Foundations

Every component is built from only five foundations.

Typography

↓

Spacing

↓

Color

↓

Motion

↓

Material

Nothing else.

Whenever a new component is proposed,

it must reuse these foundations.

---

# 17.5 Component DNA

Every Vivah component shares these characteristics.

Soft corners.

Comfortable spacing.

Warm colors.

Restrained shadows.

Natural motion.

Excellent accessibility.

Predictable behaviour.

Every component should feel handcrafted.

Not generated.

---

# 17.6 Component Hierarchy

Every component belongs to one category.

Primitive

Examples

Button

Input

Icon

Checkbox

Radio

Divider

---

Composite

Examples

Search Bar

Navigation

Card

Dropdown

Toast

Modal

---

Complex

Examples

Profile Card

Match Card

Hero

Chat Window

Dashboard Panel

Timeline

Never blur these boundaries.

---

# 17.7 Component Naming

Every component follows one naming convention.

Examples

Button

ButtonGroup

ProfileCard

HeroSection

SearchInput

NotificationItem

VerificationBadge

ConversationCard

Avoid vague names.

Examples to avoid

Card2

NewCard

HeroUpdated

ButtonV3

Names should describe purpose.

Not history.

---

# 17.8 Variants

Every component may have variants.

Example

Button

Primary

Secondary

Ghost

Text

Danger

Premium

Every variant must inherit from one parent component.

Never duplicate components.

---

# 17.9 States

Every interactive component supports

Default

Hover

Focused

Pressed

Disabled

Loading

Success (when applicable)

Error (when applicable)

No state may be forgotten.

---

# 17.10 Component Anatomy

Every component must document

Purpose

Structure

Spacing

Typography

States

Accessibility

Animation

Responsive behaviour

Usage examples

Anti-patterns

Engineering notes

No undocumented component enters production.

---

# 17.11 Internal Spacing

All internal spacing uses the spacing scale.

Never invent values.

Preferred scale

```text
4

8

12

16

24

32

48

64
```

Everything derives from this rhythm.

---

# 17.12 Corner Radius

Every component consumes radius tokens.

Examples

Buttons

12px

Cards

20px

Dialogs

24px

Inputs

14px

Never mix arbitrary radii.

---

# 17.13 Elevation

Every component belongs to one elevation level.

Level 0

Flat

Level 1

Input

Level 2

Card

Level 3

Dropdown

Level 4

Dialog

Level 5

Global Overlay

Elevation communicates hierarchy.

Nothing else.

---

# 17.14 Borders

Borders remain subtle.

Preferred

1px

Warm Gray

Very low opacity.

Avoid

Dark borders.

Multiple borders.

Double outlines.

Heavy strokes.

---

# 17.15 Motion Consistency

Every component follows the Motion Language defined earlier.

No component introduces unique easing.

No component introduces unique duration.

Every transition uses motion tokens.

---

# 17.16 Interaction Philosophy

Components respond immediately.

Feedback begins within

100 milliseconds.

The user should never wonder

"Did my click work?"

---

# 17.17 Responsive Behaviour

Components are responsive by design.

Not by scaling.

Desktop

Comfortable.

Tablet

Focused.

Mobile

Essential.

Each breakpoint is intentionally designed.

---

# 17.18 Accessibility Contract

Every interactive component guarantees

Keyboard support.

Visible focus.

Screen reader compatibility.

Touch targets.

Reduced motion.

Semantic HTML.

No exceptions.

---

# 17.19 Component Relationships

Components should compose naturally.

Example

```text
Card

├── Avatar

├── Typography

├── Badge

├── Button

├── Divider

└── Metadata
```

Never rebuild primitives inside larger components.

Reuse.

---

# 17.20 Empty States

Every complex component documents

Loading.

Empty.

Error.

Offline.

Disabled.

Success.

Every possible experience must be intentionally designed.

---

# 17.21 Error Philosophy

Components fail gracefully.

Missing image

↓

Placeholder.

Failed request

↓

Retry.

Invalid input

↓

Explanation.

No component should collapse unexpectedly.

---

# 17.22 Component Lifespan

Every component should remain useful for years.

Ask

"Will this component still feel correct after five years?"

If uncertain,

simplify it.

---

# 17.23 Theme Support

The design system should support future themes.

Current

Vivah Light.

Future

Festive.

Wedding.

Accessibility.

Dark (if ever introduced).

Themes change tokens.

Never component logic.

---

# 17.24 Documentation Standard

Every component receives its own documentation page.

Required sections

Purpose

Usage

Variants

Properties

States

Accessibility

Examples

Code

Do

Don't

Future Improvements

Components without documentation are considered incomplete.

---

# 17.25 Component Testing

Every component must pass

Visual tests.

Accessibility tests.

Responsive tests.

Interaction tests.

Keyboard tests.

Reduced motion tests.

Regression tests.

Quality is part of the component.

Not an afterthought.

---

# 17.26 Performance Budget

Each component should render efficiently.

Goals

Minimal re-renders.

GPU-friendly animations.

Lazy loading when appropriate.

Small bundle size.

Tree-shakeable imports.

No unnecessary dependencies.

A beautiful component that harms performance is a failed component.

---

# 17.27 Engineering Rules

Every component should

Be composable.

Be predictable.

Be reusable.

Be testable.

Be accessible.

Be typed.

Be documented.

Avoid side effects.

Keep business logic outside presentation whenever possible.

---

# 17.28 Anti-Patterns

Never create

One-off buttons.

One-off cards.

Page-specific components.

Hardcoded colors.

Hardcoded spacing.

Inline animation values.

Custom shadows.

Random border radii.

Every deviation weakens the design system.

---

# 17.29 Global Design Tokens

```css
/* Colors */

--color-primary

--color-secondary

--color-accent

--color-surface

--color-background

--color-border

/* Typography */

--font-display

--font-body

--font-size-xs

--font-size-sm

--font-size-md

--font-size-lg

--font-size-xl

/* Spacing */

--space-4

--space-8

--space-12

--space-16

--space-24

--space-32

--space-48

--space-64

--space-96

--space-128

/* Radius */

--radius-sm

--radius-md

--radius-lg

--radius-xl

/* Elevation */

--shadow-1

--shadow-2

--shadow-3

--shadow-4

/* Motion */

--duration-fast

--duration-normal

--duration-slow

--ease-standard

--ease-soft
```

These tokens are immutable foundations.

Components consume them.

They never redefine them.

---

# 17.30 Component Review Checklist

Before approving any new component

□ Does it solve a real problem?

□ Can an existing component solve this instead?

□ Does it follow every design token?

□ Is it accessible?

□ Is it responsive?

□ Is it documented?

□ Is it reusable?

□ Does it follow the motion language?

□ Does it feel like it belongs to Vivah?

□ Could another engineer understand and extend it six months from now?

If any answer is "No,"

the component is not ready for inclusion in the design system.

---

# 17.31 The Golden Rule

**A component should never express its own personality.**

It should express the personality of **Vivah**.

When hundreds of components work together with restraint and consistency,

the interface disappears,

and what remains is trust.

---

# End of Chapter 17

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume IV — Design System Components

# Chapter 18 — Button System

---

# 18.1 Philosophy

Buttons are promises.

Every button tells the user:

> "If you trust me with this action, I will do exactly what I say."

Buttons are therefore the highest-trust interactive component in Vivah.

They should never create uncertainty.

They should never surprise.

They should never compete with one another.

A button exists to communicate confidence.

Not urgency.

---

# 18.2 Core Principles

Every button must satisfy six principles.

Clear

↓

Predictable

↓

Accessible

↓

Comfortable

↓

Elegant

↓

Immediate

If any principle is compromised,

the button should be redesigned.

---

# 18.3 Button Hierarchy

Vivah contains only six button types.

No additional styles are permitted without updating this Design Bible.

---

## Primary Button

Purpose

The single most important action on the screen.

Examples

Create Profile

Continue

Send Interest

Start Conversation

Save Changes

Only one Primary Button should exist within a major viewport.

---

## Secondary Button

Purpose

Supporting action.

Examples

Learn More

View Details

Preview Profile

Save for Later

---

## Ghost Button

Purpose

Low-emphasis actions.

Examples

Cancel

Back

Skip

Close

Ghost buttons should never visually compete with Primary Buttons.

---

## Text Button

Purpose

Inline navigation.

Examples

Forgot Password

View All

Read Story

See More

---

## Danger Button

Purpose

Destructive actions.

Examples

Delete Account

Block User

Remove Photo

Cancel Membership

Danger buttons should appear rarely.

---

## Premium Button

Purpose

Premium membership actions.

Examples

Upgrade Membership

Unlock Premium

View Premium Benefits

Reserved exclusively for monetization.

---

# 18.4 Visual Identity

Primary

Warm Champagne

↓

Soft Shadow

↓

Rounded Corners

↓

White Typography

Secondary

White Surface

↓

Champagne Border

↓

Charcoal Typography

Ghost

Transparent

↓

Minimal Hover

↓

No Border

Premium

Subtle Metallic Gradient

↓

Champagne Highlight

↓

Very Restrained Glow

Danger

Muted Red

↓

Soft Border

↓

No Bright Red

---

# 18.5 Dimensions

Small

Height

40px

Default

48px

Large

56px

Hero

64px

Never exceed

64px.

Buttons should feel refined.

Not oversized.

---

# 18.6 Corner Radius

Small

10px

Default

14px

Large

18px

Hero

20px

Buttons should echo the softness of architecture,

not the roundness of toys.

---

# 18.7 Padding

Small

12 × 20

Default

16 × 28

Large

18 × 36

Hero

22 × 44

Padding should create comfortable touch targets.

Not visual bulk.

---

# 18.8 Typography

Font

Inter

Weight

600

Letter Spacing

0.02em

Case

Title Case

Never use ALL CAPS.

Buttons should speak politely.

---

# 18.9 Icons

Buttons may include icons.

Placement

Leading

or

Trailing

Never both.

Icon spacing

12px

Icons should remain secondary to text.

---

# 18.10 States

Every button supports

Default

↓

Hover

↓

Pressed

↓

Focused

↓

Loading

↓

Disabled

↓

Success (optional)

↓

Error (optional)

Every state must be intentionally designed.

---

# 18.11 Hover

Hover communicates readiness.

Allowed

Slight elevation.

Border refinement.

Tiny brightness shift.

Small shadow increase.

Forbidden

Glow.

Rotation.

Bounce.

Large scaling.

Hover should never distract.

---

# 18.12 Press

Press should feel physical.

Sequence

Shadow softens.

↓

Surface compresses

(≈0.98 scale)

↓

Color deepens slightly.

↓

Action executes.

↓

Surface returns naturally.

---

# 18.13 Focus

Focus remains visible.

Appearance

Champagne outline.

Soft shadow.

4px offset.

Keyboard users should feel equally welcomed.

---

# 18.14 Disabled

Disabled buttons should communicate

Unavailable.

Not broken.

Characteristics

Reduced opacity.

No hover.

No shadow.

No motion.

Readable label.

Avoid extremely faded buttons.

---

# 18.15 Loading

Loading buttons prevent duplicate actions.

Sequence

Label

↓

Spinner appears

↓

Button width remains unchanged

↓

Action completes

↓

Original label returns

Never allow button resizing.

Layout should remain stable.

---

# 18.16 Success

Certain actions deserve confirmation.

Examples

Profile Saved

Interest Sent

Verification Submitted

Payment Successful

Feedback

Checkmark replaces spinner.

Gentle fade.

No confetti.

No fireworks.

---

# 18.17 Width Rules

Buttons should size according to content.

Preferred

Intrinsic width.

Full-width only when

Mobile forms.

Authentication.

Checkout.

Critical onboarding.

Avoid unnecessarily wide buttons.

---

# 18.18 Hero Buttons

Hero buttons communicate beginnings.

Primary

Start Your Journey

Secondary

Learn More

Maximum

Two hero actions.

Never more.

---

# 18.19 Button Groups

Primary always appears first.

Desktop

Horizontal

Mobile

Vertical

Spacing

16px

Hierarchy must remain obvious.

---

# 18.20 Destructive Actions

Danger buttons should always require confirmation.

Examples

Delete Profile.

Remove Account.

Block User.

Delete Conversation.

Confirmation should explain consequences.

---

# 18.21 Premium Button

Premium buttons should communicate craftsmanship.

Never greed.

Characteristics

Subtle champagne gradient.

Fine metallic border.

Warm highlight.

No aggressive shine.

Premium should feel aspirational.

Not flashy.

---

# 18.22 Motion

Buttons follow the global Motion Language.

Hover

150ms

Press

100ms

Release

150ms

Loading

Continuous but subtle.

No component-specific timing.

---

# 18.23 Accessibility

Minimum touch target

48 × 48px

Readable labels.

Keyboard accessible.

Visible focus.

Screen reader support.

Never rely on icon-only buttons without accessible labels.

---

# 18.24 Copywriting

Button labels begin with verbs.

Preferred

Continue

Save Profile

View Matches

Start Conversation

Verify Identity

Avoid

Click Here

Go

Submit

Okay

Yes

Labels should communicate outcomes.

---

# 18.25 Mobile Behaviour

Buttons remain easy to reach.

Important actions should stay within the natural thumb zone.

Avoid placing primary actions at unreachable screen edges.

---

# 18.26 Engineering Specification

Buttons expose

Variant

Size

State

Leading Icon

Trailing Icon

Loading

Disabled

Full Width

Type

No page-specific button implementations are permitted.

---

# 18.27 CSS Tokens

```css
/* Heights */

--button-height-sm: 40px;

--button-height-md: 48px;

--button-height-lg: 56px;

--button-height-xl: 64px;

/* Padding */

--button-padding-sm;

--button-padding-md;

--button-padding-lg;

/* Radius */

--button-radius;

/* Motion */

--button-duration-hover;

--button-duration-press;

/* Shadows */

--button-shadow-default;

--button-shadow-hover;

--button-shadow-active;

/* Colors */

--button-primary-bg;

--button-primary-text;

--button-secondary-bg;

--button-secondary-border;

--button-danger-bg;

--button-premium-bg;
```

Buttons consume tokens.

Buttons never define visual values themselves.

---

# 18.28 Anti-Patterns

Reject immediately

Buttons with gradients spanning multiple colors.

Neon buttons.

Pill-shaped buttons.

Oversized floating CTAs.

Animated glowing buttons.

Multiple primary buttons.

Tiny touch targets.

Uppercase labels.

Icon-only primary buttons.

Buttons with more than one animation.

Buttons that shift surrounding layout during loading.

---

# 18.29 Review Checklist

Before approving any button

□ Is its purpose immediately obvious?

□ Does it follow the correct hierarchy?

□ Is there only one primary button per viewport?

□ Does it communicate trust?

□ Is it accessible?

□ Is the loading state stable?

□ Does the copy describe the outcome?

□ Does it follow the motion language?

□ Could this button exist in every part of Vivah without redesign?

□ Would it still feel elegant in five years?

If any answer is "No,"

the button requires refinement.

---

# 18.30 The Final Principle

A great button does not ask users to click.

It gives them the confidence to do so.

Every button in Vivah should feel like a courteous invitation—

never a demand.

---

# End of Chapter 18

# 📖 Vivah Design Bible v2.0

# Volume IV — Design System Components

# Chapter 19 — Input System & Form Experience

---

# 19.1 Philosophy

Forms are conversations.

Not paperwork.

Every input field represents a question Vivah asks with respect.

Users should never feel interrogated.

They should feel guided.

Every field should reduce uncertainty rather than create it.

Completing a form should feel like talking to a thoughtful person—not filling out a government document.

---

# 19.2 Purpose

The Input System exists to accomplish five objectives.

Collect Information

↓

Reduce Friction

↓

Build Trust

↓

Prevent Errors

↓

Encourage Completion

If an input creates anxiety,

it has failed its purpose.

---

# 19.3 Form Personality

Vivah forms should feel

Patient.

Supportive.

Professional.

Warm.

Encouraging.

Never

Corporate.

Cold.

Technical.

Mechanical.

Forms should feel like someone helping,

not someone judging.

---

# 19.4 Input Hierarchy

Vivah supports only these input primitives.

Text Input

Email Input

Password Input

Search Input

Textarea

Dropdown

Autocomplete

Date Picker

Phone Number

OTP Input

Checkbox

Radio

Switch

Slider

File Upload

No additional input type should be invented unless absolutely necessary.

---

# 19.5 Anatomy

Every input consists of

```text
Label

↓

Helper Text (optional)

↓

Input Field

↓

Validation Message

↓

Supporting Hint (optional)
```

Every layer has a purpose.

Nothing is decorative.

---

# 19.6 Labels

Labels are mandatory.

Never replace labels with placeholders.

Preferred

Full Name

Email Address

Profession

Religion

Current City

Avoid

Name

Mail

Job

Location

Labels should remove ambiguity.

---

# 19.7 Helper Text

Helper text explains.

Not repeats.

Example

Height

"Used only to improve match recommendations."

Good helper text reduces hesitation.

---

# 19.8 Placeholder Text

Placeholders provide examples.

Not instructions.

Correct

"e.g. Software Engineer"

Incorrect

"Enter your profession"

Never rely on placeholders for accessibility.

---

# 19.9 Input Dimensions

Small

44px

Default

52px

Large

60px

Touch targets should always remain comfortable.

---

# 19.10 Border Philosophy

Default

1px Warm Gray

Hover

Champagne Border

Focused

Champagne Outline

Error

Muted Red

Success

Muted Green

Borders communicate state.

Not decoration.

---

# 19.11 Corner Radius

Text Inputs

14px

Dropdowns

16px

Search

18px

Textarea

16px

OTP

12px

All inputs belong to the same family.

---

# 19.12 Typography

Label

14px

Medium

Input

16px

Regular

Helper

14px

Caption

12px

Forms should always prioritize readability.

---

# 19.13 Focus Behaviour

Focus should feel welcoming.

Sequence

Border refines.

↓

Outline appears.

↓

Shadow softens.

↓

Cursor becomes active.

Nothing should jump.

Nothing should flash.

---

# 19.14 Validation

Validation should happen intelligently.

Preferred

After field completion.

After pause.

On submission.

Avoid validating while users are actively typing.

Interruptions increase frustration.

---

# 19.15 Success States

Completed fields communicate confidence.

Examples

✓ Email verified

✓ Username available

✓ Phone number confirmed

Feedback should remain subtle.

Never celebratory.

---

# 19.16 Error States

Every error explains three things.

What happened.

↓

Why.

↓

How to fix it.

Example

Incorrect

"Invalid Phone Number"

Preferred

"Please enter a valid 10-digit mobile number."

---

# 19.17 Required Fields

Required fields use

Small asterisk.

or

"(Required)"

Never use bright red.

The form should remain calm.

---

# 19.18 Optional Fields

Optional fields should be clearly identified.

Example

Bio

(Optional)

Users should never wonder whether something is mandatory.

---

# 19.19 Search Field

Search deserves special treatment.

Features

Instant focus.

Recent searches.

Suggested searches.

Clear button.

Keyboard shortcuts.

Search should encourage exploration.

Not precision.

---

# 19.20 Password Field

Features

Visibility toggle.

Strength indicator.

Requirements.

Confirmation.

Paste allowed.

Never block password managers.

---

# 19.21 OTP Input

OTP should support

Paste.

Auto-advance.

Backspace navigation.

Mobile autofill.

No unnecessary animation.

Verification should feel effortless.

---

# 19.22 Date Picker

Dates should remain human-friendly.

Examples

15 March 2000

Not

2000-03-15

Calendar navigation should be simple.

Touch-friendly.

Keyboard accessible.

---

# 19.23 Dropdowns

Dropdowns should prioritize discovery.

Features

Search (when long).

Grouping.

Keyboard navigation.

Clear selection.

No scrolling fatigue.

---

# 19.24 Autocomplete

Suggestions should feel helpful.

Not intrusive.

Ranking

Recent.

Relevant.

Nearby.

Popular.

Alphabetical.

Never random.

---

# 19.25 File Upload

Uploading photographs should feel reassuring.

Sequence

Choose.

↓

Preview.

↓

Upload.

↓

Processing.

↓

Complete.

Never upload silently.

Users deserve visibility.

---

# 19.26 Image Upload

Photo upload should include

Preview.

Crop.

Rotate.

Replace.

Delete.

Progress.

Guidance.

Users should always know which image becomes primary.

---

# 19.27 Long Forms

Long forms should become journeys.

Break into logical sections.

Example

Basic Information

↓

Education

↓

Profession

↓

Family

↓

Lifestyle

↓

Preferences

↓

Review

Progress reduces anxiety.

---

# 19.28 Auto Save

Whenever possible,

forms should save automatically.

Visual confirmation

"Saved"

should appear quietly.

Users should never fear losing progress.

---

# 19.29 Multi-Step Forms

Every step should answer

Where am I?

↓

What remains?

↓

What happens next?

Users should never feel lost.

---

# 19.30 Keyboard Experience

Forms should support

Tab.

Shift + Tab.

Enter.

Arrow keys.

Escape.

Paste.

Autocomplete.

Professional users expect efficient keyboard workflows.

---

# 19.31 Mobile Forms

Mobile receives special optimisation.

Large fields.

Comfortable spacing.

Appropriate keyboard types.

Sticky Continue button (only during onboarding).

Avoid zoom caused by tiny text.

---

# 19.32 Accessibility

Every field requires

Label.

Programmatic association.

Error announcement.

Focus visibility.

Touch target.

Semantic HTML.

No exceptions.

---

# 19.33 Emotional Language

Instead of

"Tell us your religion."

Prefer

"Help us understand what matters to you."

Instead of

"Upload documents."

Prefer

"Help us verify your profile so others can trust it."

Language changes emotional perception.

---

# 19.34 Empty Form Philosophy

An empty form should feel full of possibility.

Not work.

Visual hierarchy.

Helpful copy.

Progress.

Examples.

Encouragement.

Forms should invite completion.

---

# 19.35 Engineering Contract

Every input exposes

Variant

Value

Disabled

Required

Invalid

Helper Text

Label

Placeholder

Prefix

Suffix

Loading

Readonly

Size

No component should implement its own validation visuals.

---

# 19.36 Design Tokens

```css
/* Heights */

--input-height-sm;

--input-height-md;

--input-height-lg;

/* Radius */

--input-radius;

/* Borders */

--input-border;

--input-border-hover;

--input-border-focus;

--input-border-error;

--input-border-success;

/* Colors */

--input-bg;

--input-text;

--input-placeholder;

--input-helper;

--input-label;

/* Motion */

--input-duration-focus;

--input-duration-hover;
```

Every input consumes shared tokens.

No visual values are hardcoded.

---

# 19.37 Anti-Patterns

Reject immediately

Placeholder-only forms.

Floating labels.

Tiny inputs.

Aggressive validation.

Bright red error messages.

Tiny dropdown arrows.

Confusing date pickers.

Multiple field styles.

Different border radii.

Dark input backgrounds.

Glass inputs.

Inputs without labels.

Unclear required fields.

---

# 19.38 Review Checklist

Before approving any form

□ Does every field have a clear purpose?

□ Are labels always visible?

□ Can the form be completed using only the keyboard?

□ Is validation helpful?

□ Does the form reduce anxiety?

□ Is progress obvious?

□ Does auto-save protect user effort?

□ Is mobile comfortable?

□ Does every field follow the design system?

□ Would someone over 60 complete this form without confusion?

If any answer is "No,"

the form is not ready for production.

---

# 19.39 The Final Principle

A great form does not feel like data collection.

It feels like the beginning of a relationship.

Every question Vivah asks should make users feel understood,

never evaluated.

---

# End of Chapter 19


